lers]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Challenge League players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich players]]\n[[Category:S.S. Lazio players]]\n[[Category:AC Bellinzona players]]\n[[Category:S.S.D. Palermo players]]\n[[Category:Fulham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Luzern players]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Sion players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Albanian descent]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Macedonian descent]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Switzerland international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pajtim_Kasami"}
{"title_page": "Edward Belcher", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|width_style = person\n|name = Sir Edward Belcher\n|honorific_suffix = {{postnom|country=GBR|size=100%|CB|KCB}}\n|image = Sir Edward Belcher by Stephen Pearce.jpg\n|image_size = 250\n|caption = Sir Edward Belcher {{circa|1859}}\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1799|02|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[City of Halifax|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]]\n|death_date = {{dda|1877|03|18|1799|02|27|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[London]], England\n|allegiance = {{flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n|branch_label = Branch\n|branch = {{navy|UKGBI}}\n|serviceyears_label = Service&nbsp;years\n|serviceyears = 1812\u20131865\n|rank = [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|commands = {{ubl|{{HMS|Sulphur|1826|6}}|{{HMS|Samarang|1822|6}}|{{HMS|Assistance|1850|6}}}}\n|battles_label = Wars\n|battles = [[First Opium War|First Anglo-Chinese War]]\n|awards = {{ubl|[[China War Medal (1842)|China War Medal]] (1842)|[[Naval Long Service and Good Conduct Medal (1848)|Long Service Medal]] (1848)|[[Arctic Medal]] (1857)}}\n|spouse = Diana Jolliffe\n}}\n[[File:Hong Kong Map made by Edward Belcher in 1841.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Belcher's map of Hong Kong, after surveying the island in 1841]]\n\nAdmiral '''Sir Edward Belcher''' {{postnom|country=GBR|CB|KCB}} (27 February 1799&nbsp;\u2013 18 March 1877) was a British naval officer, [[hydrographer]], and explorer.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Obituary. Admiral Sir Edward Belcher, K.C.B.|url=https://archive.org/details/belcherobituary1877vol212015.530426.proceedingsof|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Geographical Society|year=1877|volume=21|pages=410\u2013416}}</ref> Born in [[Nova Scotia]], he was the great-grandson of Governor [[Jonathan Belcher]]. He was briefly married to Diana Jolliffe, stepdaughter of Captain [[Peter Heywood]], that marriage ending upon her application for legal separation for his having infected her with venereal disease.<ref>''Dictionary of Hong Kong Biography'', Hong Kong University Press 2012, p. 24.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nBelcher was born in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], the second son of [[Andrew Belcher (merchant)|Andrew Belcher]] and entered the [[Royal Navy]] in 1812.\n\n===Surveys===\nIn 1825, he accompanied [[Frederick William Beechey]]'s expedition to the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] and [[Bering Strait]] as a [[Surveyor (surveying)|surveyor]]<ref name=\"Ritchie\">{{cite book |last1=Ritchie |first1=G.S. |title=The Admiralty Chart |date=1967 |publisher=Hollis & Carter |location=London}}</ref>{{rp|153}}. In 1836. he commanded a surveying ship on the north and west coasts of Africa and in the British seas. Belcher took up the work which Beechey had left unfinished on the Pacific coast of [[South America]]. He was on board {{HMS|Sulphur|1826|6}}, which was ordered to return to England in 1839 via the Trans-Pacific route. Belcher made various observations at a number of islands which he visited, having been delayed by being despatched to take part in the [[First Opium War|war in China]] in 1840.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nOn 25 January 1841, Commander Belcher landed on [[Possession Point]] at the north shore [[Hong Kong Island]] and made the first British survey of [[Hong Kong]] harbour. After the war's end in 1842 he reached home and for his services was made a [[Knight Bachelor]] in the following year. He was then engaged on {{HMS|Samarang|1822|6}}, in surveying work in the [[East Indies]], the Philippines, [[Port Hamilton]], and other places, until 1847.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n===Arctic expedition===\nIn 1852 Belcher led the last and largest Admiralty expedition to rescue [[Sir John Franklin]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} He was also to look for his former surveying officer in Hong Kong, [[Richard Collinson|Sir Richard Collinson]], and [[Robert McClure|Sir Robert McClure]], whose ships had not been seen after entering the Bering Strait. He did a great deal of sledge exploration, rescued McClure and abandoned four of his five ships in the ice.\n\nHe had five ships: {{HMS|Assistance|1850|6}} (Belcher), {{HMS|Resolute|1850|6}} ([[Henry Kellett]], second mate [[George Nares]]), the steam tenders ''Pioneer'' ([[Sherard Osborn]]) and ''Intrepid'' ([[Leopold McClintock|Sir Leopold McClintock]]) and the depot ship {{HMS|North Star|1824|6}} ([[William Pullen]]). Belcher and one tender were to enter [[Wellington Channel]], where Franklin was thought to be, while Kellett was to go west to [[Melville Island (Arctic)|Melville Island]] and look for Collinson and McClure. ''North Star'' was to stay at [[Beechey Island]] as a supply base.\n\nHe left the [[Nore]] in April 1850. By early winter ''Assistance'' and ''Pioneer'' were frozen in at [[Northumberland Sound]] to the north of Wellington Channel while ''Resolute'' and ''Intrepid'' were frozen in off Melville Island &mdash;the first ships this far West since [[Sir William Edward Parry]] in 1819. A great deal of exploration was done by [[manhauling|manhauled]] sledges. In April 1853 [[Leopold McClintock]] and others left ''Resolute'' on sledges and returned 105&nbsp;days later, having covered {{convert|1400|mi|km}} and discovered [[Prince Patrick Island]].\n\nAnother party went West and discovered Robert McClure, whose ship was frozen in at [[Mercy Bay]]. Belcher went north by sledge and found a channel at the northern tip of [[Devon Island]], hinting that Franklin might have used it to escape to [[Baffin Bay]]. When the ice broke up that summer, he pushed his ships up Wellington Channel and became trapped again.\n\nBy February 1854, Belcher was becoming increasingly worried about the safety of his ships and men. In April he ordered Kellett to abandon his ships and return by sledge to ''North Star''. Belcher abandoned his two ships in late July. Aided by two ships that showed up at Beechey Island ({{HMS|Phoenix|1832|2}} and {{ship||Breadalbane|ship|2}}), the whole party returned to England. Belcher went through a [[court martial]], which was automatic for any captain who had lost a ship.\n[[File:WilliamsNorthStar1845.jpg|thumb|right|''H M S North Star destroying Pomare's P\u0101, 1845.'' Painting by John Williams.<ref name=\"ANZ\">{{cite web| last =Roger| first = Blackley|title= Lance-Sergeant John Williams: Military Topographer of the Northern War| publisher=Art New Zealand no.32|pages =50\u201353|date=1984|url= http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues31to40/williams.htm| accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Lossy-page1-4800px-H.M.S Resolute and Intrepid winter Quarters, Melville Island, 1852-53 RMG PU6194 (cropped).jpg|thumb|HMS ''Resolute'' and ''Intrepid'' winter quarters, Melville Island, 1852\u201353]]\n[[File:'Assistance' and 'Pioneer' breaking out of winter quarters,1854 RMG PW8119.tiff|thumb|right|HMS ''Assistance'' and ''Pioneer'' breaking out of winter quarters, 1854]]\n\nHe was exonerated, but his sword was returned to him \"without observation\". He never again received an active command. Curiously ''Resolute'' broke free of the ice and drifted all the way to [[Davis Strait]], where it was picked up by an American [[Whaling ship|whaler]]. The American government graciously returned the ship to the United Kingdom, and when many years later the ship was [[Ship breaking|broken up]], its timbers were used to make a desk for the American president by way of a thank you. This [[Resolute desk|''Resolute'' desk]], a gift from [[Queen Victoria]], is still used today in the [[Oval Office]].\n\n===Later life===\nFollowing his last active service, Belcher was appointed Knight Commander of the [[Order of the Bath]] in 1867, and an admiral in 1872.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nBelcher is commemorated in Hong Kong through [[Belcher's Street]], [[Belcher Bay]] and [[The Belcher's]] in [[Kennedy Town]]. His name is also commemorated in the [[Belcher Islands]], in the [[Canadian Arctic]]. He is also commemorated with a plaque in the Admiralty Garden, [[CFB Halifax]].\n\nA highly venomous [[Hydrophiinae|seasnake]], ''[[Hydrophis belcheri]]'', is also named in his honour.<ref>Beolens, Bo; Watkins, Michael; Grayson, Michael (2011). ''The Eponym Dictionary of Reptiles''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. {{ISBN|9781421401355}}. (Belcher, p.&nbsp;22.)</ref> Belcher collected the [[holotype]] which is housed in the [[Natural History Museum, London]].\n\n==Works==\n* ''Treatise on Nautical Surveying'' (1835)\n* ''Narrative of a Voyage Round the World'' (1843). ([https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag01belc Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag02belc Vol. 2]).\n* ''Narrative of the Voyage of H.M.S. Samarang, During the Years 1843\u201346'' (1848). ([https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag01belciala Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag02belciala Vol. 2]).\n* ''The Last of the Arctic Voyages'' (1855). ([https://archive.org/details/lastofarcticvoya01belc Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/lastofarcticvoya02belc_0 Vol. 2]).\n* ''Horatio Howard Brenton'' (1856). ([https://books.google.com/books?id=9bEBAAAAQAAJ Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/horatiohowardbre02belc Vol. 2] / [https://archive.org/details/horatiohowardbre03belc Vol. 3]).\n\n==See also==\n* [[European and American voyages of scientific exploration]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Belcher, Sir Edward|volume=3|page=663}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Coleman|first=E. C.|year=2007|title=The Royal Navy and Polar exploration: from Franklin to Scott|location=Stroud|publisher=Tempus |isbn=0-7524-4207-4|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Alexander|first=Caroline|year=2003|isbn=0-670-03133-X|publisher=Viking |location=New York |title=The Bounty: The True Story of the Mutiny on the Bounty |postscript=<!--None--> |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/bountytruestoryo00alex }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikisource author}}\n* {{BHL author}}\n* {{OL author}}\n* {{Internet Archive author}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n50082934}}\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/2667 Edward Belcher Notebook, 1860] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n{{Polar exploration}}\n{{Royal Navy Arctic exploration}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Belcher, Edward}}\n[[Category:1799 births]]\n[[Category:1877 deaths]]\n[[Category:British polar explorers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Explorers of the Arctic]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:People from Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Persons of National Historic Significance (Canada)]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Napoleonic Wars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|width_style = person\n|name = Sir Edward Belcher\n|honorific_suffix = {{postnom|country=GBR|size=100%|CB|KCB}}\n|image = Sir Edward Belcher by Stephen Pearce.jpg\n|image_size = 250\n|caption = Sir Edward Belcher {{circa|1859}}\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1799|02|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[City of Halifax|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]]\n|death_date = {{dda|1877|03|18|1799|02|27|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[London]], England\n|allegiance = {{flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n|branch_label = Branch\n|branch = {{navy|UKGBI}}\n|serviceyears_label = Service&nbsp;years\n|serviceyears = 1812\u20131865\n|rank = [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|commands = {{ubl|{{HMS|Sulphur|1826|6}}|{{HMS|Samarang|1822|6}}|{{HMS|Assistance|1850|6}}}}\n|battles_label = Wars\n|battles = [[First Opium War|First Anglo-Chinese War]]\n|awards = {{ubl|[[China War Medal (1842)|China War Medal]] (1842)|[[Naval Long Service and Good Conduct Medal (1848)|Long Service Medal]] (1848)|[[Arctic Medal]] (1857)}}\n|spouse = Diana Jolliffe\n}}\n[[File:Hong Kong Map made by Edward Belcher in 1841.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Belcher's map of Hong Kong, after surveying the island in 1841]]\n\nAdmiral '''Sir Edward Belcher''' {{postnom|country=GBR|CB|KCB}} (27 February 1799&nbsp;\u2013 18 March 1877) was a British naval officer, [[hydrographer]], and explorer.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Obituary. Admiral Sir Edward Belcher, K.C.B.|url=https://archive.org/details/belcherobituary1877vol212015.530426.proceedingsof|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Geographical Society|year=1877|volume=21|pages=410\u2013416}}</ref> Born in [[Nova Scotia]], he was the great-grandson of Governor [[Jonathan Belcher]]. He was briefly married to Diana Jolliffe, stepdaughter of Captain [[Peter Heywood]], that marriage ending upon her application for legal separation for his having infected her with venereal disease.<ref>''Dictionary of Hong Kong Biography'', Hong Kong University Press 2012, p. 24.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nBelcher was born in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]], the second son of [[Andrew Belcher (merchant)|Andrew Belcher]] and entered the [[Royal Navy]] in 1812.\n\n===Surveys===\nIn 1825, he accompanied [[Frederick William Beechey]]'s expedition to the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] and [[Bering Strait]] as a [[Surveyor (surveying)|surveyor]]<ref name=\"Ritchie\">{{cite book |last1=Ritchie |first1=G.S. |title=The Admiralty Chart |date=1967 |publisher=Hollis & Carter |location=London}}</ref>{{rp|153}}. In 1836. he commanded a surveying ship on the north and west coasts of Africa and in the British seas. Belcher took up the work which Beechey had left unfinished on the Pacific coast of [[South America]]. He was on board {{HMS|Sulphur|1826|6}}, which was ordered to return to England in 1839 via the Trans-Pacific route. Belcher made various observations at a number of islands which he visited, having been delayed by being despatched to take part in the [[First Opium War|war in China]] in 1840.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nOn 25 January 1841, Commander Belcher landed on [[Possession Point]] at the north shore [[Hong Kong Island]] and made the first British survey of [[Hong Kong]] harbour. After the war's end in 1842 he reached home and for his services was made a [[Knight Bachelor]] in the following year. He was then engaged on {{HMS|Samarang|1822|6}}, in surveying work in the [[East Indies]], the Philippines, [[Port Hamilton]], and other places, until 1847.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n===Arctic expedition===\nIn 1852 Belcher led the last and largest Admiralty expedition to rescue [[Sir John Franklin]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} He was also to look for his former surveying officer in Hong Kong, [[Richard Collinson|Sir Richard Collinson]], and [[Robert McClure|Sir Robert McClure]], whose ships had not been seen after entering the Bering Strait. He did a great deal of sledge exploration, rescued McClure and abandoned four of his five ships in the ice.\n\nHe had five ships: {{HMS|Assistance|1850|6}} (Belcher), {{HMS|Resolute|1850|6}} ([[Henry Kellett]], second mate [[George Nares]]), the steam tenders ''Pioneer'' ([[Sherard Osborn]]) and ''Intrepid'' ([[Leopold McClintock|Sir Leopold McClintock]]) and the depot ship {{HMS|North Star|1824|6}} ([[William Pullen]]). Belcher and one tender were to enter [[Wellington Channel]], where Franklin was thought to be, while Kellett was to go west to [[Melville Island (Arctic)|Melville Island]] and look for Collinson and McClure. ''North Star'' was to stay at [[Beechey Island]] as a supply base.\n\nHe left the [[Nore]] in April 1850. By early winter ''Assistance'' and ''Pioneer'' were frozen in at [[Northumberland Sound]] to the north of Wellington Channel while ''Resolute'' and ''Intrepid'' were frozen in off Melville Island &mdash;the first ships this far West since [[Sir William Edward Parry]] in 1819. A great deal of exploration was done by [[manhauling|manhauled]] sledges. In April 1853 [[Leopold McClintock]] and others left ''Resolute'' on sledges and returned 105&nbsp;days later, having covered {{convert|1400|mi|km}} and discovered [[Prince Patrick Island]].\n\nAnother party went West and discovered Robert McClure, whose ship was frozen in at [[Mercy Bay]]. Belcher went north by sledge and found a channel at the northern tip of [[Devon Island]], hinting that Franklin might have used it to escape to [[Baffin Bay]]. When the ice broke up that summer, he pushed his ships up Wellington Channel and became trapped again.\n\nBy February 1854, Belcher was becoming increasingly worried about the safety of his ships and men. In April he ordered Kellett to abandon his ships and return by sledge to ''North Star''. Belcher abandoned his two ships in late July. Aided by two ships that showed up at Beechey Island ({{HMS|Phoenix|1832|2}} and {{ship||Breadalbane|ship|2}}), the whole party returned to England. Belcher went through a [[court martial]], which was automatic for any captain who had lost a ship.\n[[File:WilliamsNorthStar1845.jpg|thumb|right|''H M S North Star destroying Pomare's P\u0101, 1845.'' Painting by John Williams.<ref name=\"ANZ\">{{cite web| last =Roger| first = Blackley|title= Lance-Sergeant John Williams: Military Topographer of the Northern War| publisher=Art New Zealand no.32|pages =50\u201353|date=1984|url= http://www.art-newzealand.com/Issues31to40/williams.htm| accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Lossy-page1-4800px-H.M.S Resolute and Intrepid winter Quarters, Melville Island, 1852-53 RMG PU6194 (cropped).jpg|thumb|HMS ''Resolute'' and ''Intrepid'' winter quarters, Melville Island, 1852\u201353]]\n[[File:'Assistance' and 'Pioneer' breaking out of winter quarters,1854 RMG PW8119.tiff|thumb|right|HMS ''Assistance'' and ''Pioneer'' breaking out of winter quarters, 1854]]\n\nHe was exonerated, but his sword was returned to him \"without observation\". He never again received an active command. Curiously ''Resolute'' broke free of the ice and drifted all the way to [[Davis Strait]], where it was picked up by an American [[Whaling ship|whaler]]. The American government graciously returned the ship to the United Kingdom, and when many years later the ship was [[Ship breaking|broken up]], its timbers were used to make a desk for the American president by way of a thank you. This [[Resolute desk|''Resolute'' desk]], a gift from [[Queen Victoria]], is still used today in the [[Oval Office]].\n\n===Later life===\nFollowing his last active service, Belcher was appointed Knight Commander of the [[Order of the Bath]] in 1867, and an admiral in 1872.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nBelcher is commemorated in Hong Kong through [[Belcher's Street]], [[Belcher Bay]] and [[The Belcher's]] in [[Kennedy Town]]. His name is also commemorated in the [[Belcher Islands]], in the [[Canadian Arctic]]. He is also commemorated with a plaque in the Admiralty Garden, [[CFB Halifax]].\n\nA highly venomous [[Hydrophiinae|seasnake]], ''[[Hydrophis belcheri]]'', is also named in his honour.<ref>Beolens, Bo; Watkins, Michael; Grayson, Michael (2011). ''The Eponym Dictionary of Reptiles''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. {{ISBN|9781421401355}}. (Belcher, p.&nbsp;22.)</ref> Belcher collected the [[holotype]] which is housed in the [[Natural History Museum, London]].\n\n==Works==\n* ''Treatise on Nautical Surveying'' (1835)\n* ''Narrative of a Voyage Round the World'' (1843). ([https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag01belc Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag02belc Vol. 2]).\n* ''Narrative of the Voyage of H.M.S. Samarang, During the Years 1843\u201346'' (1848). ([https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag01belciala Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/narrativeofvoyag02belciala Vol. 2]).\n* ''The Last of the Arctic Voyages'' (1855). ([https://archive.org/details/lastofarcticvoya01belc Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/lastofarcticvoya02belc_0 Vol. 2]).\n* ''Horatio Howard Brenton'' (1856). ([https://books.google.com/books?id=9bEBAAAAQAAJ Vol. 1] / [https://archive.org/details/horatiohowardbre02belc Vol. 2] / [https://archive.org/details/horatiohowardbre03belc Vol. 3]).\n\n==See also==\n* [[European and American voyages of scientific exploration]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Belcher, Sir Edward|volume=3|page=663}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Coleman|first=E. C.|year=2007|title=The Royal Navy and Polar exploration: from Franklin to Scott|location=Stroud|publisher=Tempus |isbn=0-7524-4207-4|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Alexander|first=Caroline|year=2003|isbn=0-670-03133-X|publisher=Viking |location=New York |title=The Bounty: The True Story of the Mutiny on the Bounty |postscript=<!--None--> |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/bountytruestoryo00alex }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikisource author}}\n* {{BHL author}}\n* {{OL author}}\n* {{Internet Archive author}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n50082934}}\n\n{{Polar exploration}}\n{{Royal Navy Arctic exploration}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Belcher, Edward}}\n[[Category:1799 births]]\n[[Category:1877 deaths]]\n[[Category:British polar explorers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Explorers of the Arctic]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:People from Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Persons of National Historic Significance (Canada)]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Napoleonic Wars]]\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added  link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Belcher"}
{"title_page": "Alan Winde", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Alan Winde\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image               = Alan Winde.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Winde in 2018\n| office              = 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]\n| status              = \n| premier             = \n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Helen Zille]]\n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]\n| premier1            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1         = 1 November 2018\n| term_end1           = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Dan Plato]]\n| successor1          = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office2             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]\n| premier2            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2         = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2           = 1 November 2018\n| alongside2          = \n| constituency2       = \n| predecessor2        = ''Position established''\n| successor2          = [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] \n| majority2           = \n| prior_term2         =\n| office3             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]\n| premier3            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2009\n| term_end3           = 26 May 2014\n| alongside3          = \n| constituency3       = \n| predecessor3        = Garth Strachan\n| successor3          = ''Position dissolved''\n| majority3           = \n| prior_term3         =\n| office4            = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start4        = 15 June 1999\n| birthname          = Alan Richard Winde\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knysna]], [[Cape Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = [[South Africa]]n\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (1999\u20132000) <br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (Before 1999)\n| spouse             = Tracy Winde (m. 1993)\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = 2\n| residence          = [[Knysna]]<br />[[Cape Town]]\n| education          = Knysna High School\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician<br />Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Alan Richard Winde''' (born 18 March 1965) is a South African politician and previous businessman.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', Western Cape, 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 30 September 2018.</ref> He is currently serving as the 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]] since his election in 2019, and a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] since 1999. He previously served as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]], the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]] and the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]. Winde is a member of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA).\n\nBorn in [[Knysna]], Winde attended Knysna High School. He has experience as a businessman and entrepreneur since he established several businesses. He also worked for and managed numerous companies. He started his political career as a municipal and district councillor in the early 1990s. Shortly afterwards in 1999, he was elected to the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He has held various leadership positions in the Democratic Alliance provincial parliament caucus. Winde was appointed [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]] in May 2009 and served until May 2014, when he assumed the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet], ''Mail & Guardian''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref><ref>Williams, Murray. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the Democratic Alliance selected Winde to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-named-da-candidate-to-take-over-from-helen-zille-as-premier/ Alan Winde named DA candidate to take over from Helen Zille as premier], ''TimesLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref> In October 2018, Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed Winde to the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]. He took office on 1 November 2018.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the Democratic Alliance retained their majority in the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]], but with a decrease in the number of seats.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-10-democratic-alliance-officially-wins-the-western-cape-vote/ It's official: The Democratic Alliance has won the Western Cape], ''TimesLIVE'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> Winde was elected Premier on 22 May 2019 and succeeded Helen Zille. He is the second Western Cape Premier from the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Le Roux |first1=Nckey |title=Winde formally elected as Premier on 22 May |url=https://www.georgeherald.com/News/Article/Elections-2019/premier-elect-inaugurated-on-22-may-201905131129 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=George Herald |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and business career==\n===Family and personal life===\nWinde was born on 18 March 1965 in the town of [[Knysna]]. He attended and matriculated from Knysna High School. He married Tracy Winde in 1993. They have two children named Lauren and Jason.<ref name = \"onesaforall\">[https://www.onesouthafricaforall.co.za/ Alan Winde], ''Democratic Alliance''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde's father, William Dave Winde, died on 1 August 2019.<ref>(In Afrikaans) [https://www.son.co.za/Nuus/Suid-Kaap/premier-se-pa-oorlede-20190801 Winde se pa oorlede], ''Son Digitaal'', 1 August 2019. Retrieved on 1 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===Business career===\nWinde has experience as an entrepreneur. He established and managed many small businesses. He was also a director of a tour company and a business broker with Aldes Business Brokers.<ref name=\"onesaforall\" />\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Minister Alan Winde (cropped).jpg|x200px|thumb|left|Winde as Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism in 2013]]\nWinde ran as an independent candidate and was elected to the South Cape District Council in 1996. He had previously served as a councillor for the Outeniqua Rural Council. Shortly after being elected a district councillor, the [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] recruited him to be a candidate for the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He was elected in the [[1999 South African general election|general election of 1999]].<ref name =\"bizzabo\">[https://events.bizzabo.com/u-start-conference-africa/agenda/speakers/89264 Alan Winde - Bizzabo], ''U-Start Conference Africa''. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe took office as a Member on 15 June 2009. During his first term, he served as Western Cape Provincial Finance Chairman and a Member of the Executive Committee. He returned to the Provincial Parliament following the 2004 general election. Briefly, before being re-elected in 2009, he served as Chief Whip of the Official Opposition, Party Spokesperson on Environment and Planning and Deputy Party Spokesperson on Economic Development and Tourism.<ref name=\"bizzabo\" />\n\nPremier Helen Zille appointed Winde to the position of Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism following his re-election in May 2009. Constitutional Court Judge [[Yvonne Mokgoro]] swore him in as Provincial Minister on 7 May 2009. He consequently succeeded Garth Strachan.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/appointment-western-cape-provincial-cabinet Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 7 May 2009. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the 2014 elections, Premier Helen Zille announced that Winde would now hold the title of Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities and only lead the Provincial Departments of Agriculture, Economic Development and Tourism. The Provincial Finance Department would be an independent department with its own Provincial Minister. Western Cape Deputy Judge President Jeanette Traverso swore him in on 26 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/premier-helen-zille-announces-new-cabinet Premier Helen Zille Announces New Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Winde was selected by the DA's Federal Executive to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate for the 2019 provincial election.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-da-names-alan-winde-western-cape-premier-candidate WATCH: DA names Alan Winde as Western Cape Premier candidate], ''eNCA'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPremier Helen Zille announced in October 2018 that Winde would move to the Provincial Community Safety Department as incumbent Provincial Minister [[Dan Plato]] had announced his intention to resign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thaw |first1=Regan |title=Alan Winde to take over WC Community Safety portfolio |url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=19 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |archivedate=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alan Winde replacing Dan Plato as community safety MEC |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/alan-winde-replacing-dan-plato-as-community-safety-mec-17553379 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> Winde was succeeded by [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] on 1 November 2018. He subsequently assumed the post of Provincial Minister of Community Safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=Western Cape Economic Development on swearing in of MEC Beverley Sch\u00e4fer |url=https://www.gov.za/speeches/western-cape-economic-development-swearing-mec-beverley-sch%C3%A4fer-1-nov-2018-0000 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |publisher=South African Government |date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nWinde has served as acting Premier of the Western Cape on various brief occasions.<ref>[https://twitter.com/alanwinde/status/1092696090162446337 Alan Winde on Twitter: \"I have just been sworn in as Acting Premier. I agreed with the Judge not to invade any neighboring country.\"]. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He represented the provincial government at the [[State of the Nation Address (South Africa)|February 2019 State of the Nation Address]], as [[Helen Zille]] was in [[Germany]].<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sona-2019-from-thuma-mina-to-new-dawn-fades-as-bosasa-casts-a-shadow-20190208 SONA 2019: From 'Thuma Mina' to 'New Dawn Fades' as Bosasa casts a shadow], News24, 8 February 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n== Premier of the Western Cape (2019\u2013present)==\n===Campaign===\n{{see also|2019 Western Cape provincial election}}\n[[File:Alan Winde For Premier Campaign Bus 2019 (cropped).jpg|270px|thumb|Alan Winde for Premier campaign bus, which was unveiled in April 2019.]]\nWinde emerged as the front-runner quite early on in the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=Who wants to be the Western Cape's next |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/who-wants-to-be-the-western-capes-next-premier-15527764 |accessdate=28 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=18 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, Democratic Alliance Federal Leader, [[Mmusi Maimane]], announced Winde as the party's Western Cape Premier candidate to succeed Premier [[Helen Zille]] after the 2019 elections. Winde defeated prominent candidates such as the Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape, [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]], and Member of Parliament [[David Maynier]]. After the announcement, Madikizela endorsed Winde and offered his full support to Winde's campaign.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', [[Western Cape]], 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Dentlinger, Lindsay. [https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/featured/da-wc-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-backs-alan-winde-as-premier-candidate/ar-BBNA1TB DA WC leader Bonginkosi Madikizela backs Alan Winde as premier candidate], ''MSN'', 20 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance launched their campaign to retain the Western Cape after the 2019 elections at the [[Cape Town Stadium]] on 29 September 2018. At the event, Mmusi Maimane highlighted the party's achievements while governing the province, such as the province's low unemployment rate and that the party had turned the previously struggling Provincial Education Department into one of the best functioning departments in South Africa.<ref>Isaacs, Lauren. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/30/da-determined-to-retain-western-cape-in-2019-elections DA determined to retain Western Cape in 2019 elections],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/unity-the-rallying-call-for-western-cape-da-as-it-launches-its-election-campaign-20180929 Unity the rallying call for Western Cape DA, as it launches its election campaign], ''News24'', 29 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter he was announced as the premier candidate, Winde embarked on a listening tour and travelled to various communities in the [[Western Cape]].<ref>[https://pr.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-DA-Western-Cape-Premier-Candidate-Winde-takes-Listening-Tour-to-George-8001073 #WindeForPremier: DA Western Cape Premier Candidate Winde takes Listening Tour to George], ''African News Agency'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nHe also campaigned for local DA candidates in by-elections. For instance, he went to the community of De Doorns to campaign for a DA candidate in a hotly-contested by-election. The DA candidate, Luwellyn Willemse, retained ward 3 of the [[Breede Valley Local Municipality|Breede Valley municipality]] by earning a total of 1,101 votes (52.16%).<ref>{{cite news |title=DA retains ward in Breede Valley municipal by-election |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2027939/da-retains-ward-in-breede-valley-municipal-by-election/ |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-Alan-Winde-to-address-supporters-at-De-Doorns-final-rally-ahead-of-by-election-7777913 #WindeForPremier: Alan Winde to address supporters at De Doorns final rally ahead of by-election], ''African News Agency''. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde launched the Democratic Alliance's 2019 provincial voter registration campaign on 4 January 2019. Winde and other Democratic Alliance members erected party registration posters in [[Mitchells Plain]], ahead of the Independent Electoral Commission's registration weekend on 26 and 27 January 2019.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-winde-launches-das-campaign-voter-registration-plan-criticised-18686993 WATCH: Winde launches DA's campaign, voter registration plan criticised], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 5 August 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance held its provincial Plan of Action Rally on 2 March 2019 at the [[Bellville Velodrome]] and launched their provincial party manifesto. Winde and various other DA politicians addressed thousands of party supporters. Winde assured that he would take on the national government for the Western Cape to receive its own, decentralised [[Rail transport in South Africa|rail]] and [[South African Police Service|police service]]. He pledged to increase the availability of [[Housing voucher|housing vouchers]] and vowed to spend [[Taxation in South Africa|tax money]] properly.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/da-comes-out-guns-blazing-to-retain-control-of-wc DA comes out guns blazing to retain control of WC], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref><ref>Payne, Sune. [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-03-04-da-punts-control-of-rail-and-policing-in-western-cape-as-party-launches-provincial-manifesto/ DA punts control of rail and policing in Western Cape as party launches provincial manifesto], ''The Daily Maverick'', 4 March 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref><ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/maimane-unemployment-will-continue-to-rise-the-longer-anc-stays-in-power Maimane: Unemployment will continue to rise the longer ANC stays in power],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde vowed on 11 March 2019 to build a police station in the gang-riddled community of [[Bonteheuwel]] due to the large number of murders that occur in the suburb.<ref>Mortlock, Monique.  \n[https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/11/winde-promises-to-a-police-station-in-bonteheuwel-if-da-wins-elections Winde promises to build police station in Bonteheuwel if DA wins elections], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde participated in the first [[eNCA]] Town Hall Debate, hosted at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]] on 14 March 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-emotions-run-high-encas-town-hall-debate WATCH: Emotions run high at eNCA's Town Hall Debate], ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref> The debate included many senior Western Cape politicians, such as former African National Congress Premier, [[Ebrahim Rasool]], Economic Freedom Fighters City of Cape Town councillor, [[Melikhaya Xego]], Good Party Leader, [[Patricia de Lille]], and Freedom Front Plus Western Cape Premier candidate, [[Peter Marais]].<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/senior-politicians-trade-barbs-campaign-at-enca-townhall-debate-in-the-capes-mitchells-plain-20190314 Senior politicians trade barbs, campaign at eNCA townhall debate in the Cape's Mitchells Plain], ''News24'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/live-video-cape-town-pre-election-town-hall-meetings WATCH: eNCA Town Hall Debate - Cape Town], Johannesburg, ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019.  Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and [[Mmusi Maimane]] revealed the Democratic Alliance's alternative energy plan for the Western Cape on 27 March 2019, in which the province acquires electricity directly from Independent Power Producers (IPPs).<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-maimane-winde-reveal-das-alternative-energy-plan-20115500 WATCH: Maimane, Winde reveal DA's alternative energy plan], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 27 March 2019. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance retained control of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, but with a decrease in the number of seats, on 8 May 2019.<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/elections/2128368/live-da-secures-majority-again-in-western-cape-election-results/ LIVE: DA secures majority again in Western Cape election results], ''The Citizen'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> The party celebrated their election win in the province on 16 May 2019.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/campaigning-a-reality-check-das-winde-admits-as-he-thanks-the-western-cape-20190516 Campaigning a 'reality check', DA's Winde admits as he thanks the Western Cape], ''News24'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved on 18 May 2019.</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWinde was elected Premier of the Western Cape on 22 May 2019 during the first sitting of the Sixth Provincial Parliament. He received 24 out of the 34 valid votes. Six ballots were spoilt, and there were two abstentions. His main challenger for the post was [[Cameron Dugmore]] of the [[African National Congress]], who received only 10 out of the 34 valid votes.<ref>Lee, Samantha. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Peoples-Post/breaking-winde-sworn-in-as-western-cape-premier-20190522 Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''News24'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>Mortlock, Monique. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/da-s-winde-elected-as-new-wc-premier DA's Winde elected as new WC premier], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2133822/winde-elected-western-cape-premier/ Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''The Citizen'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde announced the formation of his Provincial Cabinet on 23 May 2019. He retained four ministers in their existing portfolios, while he moved three to other portfolios and appointed three new members. He appointed former DA Member of Parliament and premier candidate contender, [[David Maynier]], to the post of Provincial Minister of Finance and Economic Opportunities, while he moved [[Albert Fritz]] and [[Ivan Meyer]] to the posts of Provincial Minister of Community Safety and Provincial Minister of Agriculture, respectively. Winde also said that all the newly-appointed cabinet members would undergo lifestyle audits.<ref name=\"provincial cabinet\">\n*Sicetsha, Andile. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/western-cape-premier-alan-winde-new-cabinet/ Western Cape Premier Alan Winde announces new Cabinet], ''The South African'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 9 September 2019.\n*Meyer, Dan. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new], ''TimesLIVE'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.\n*[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-names-western-cape-cabinet-20190523 Winde names new Western Cape cabinet], ''News24'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Nkanjeni, Unathi. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-24-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-western-cape-provincial-cabinet/ What you need to know about the Western Cape provincial cabinet], ''TimesLIVE'', 24 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Kiewit, Lester. [https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-23-windes-cabinet-to-undergo-lifestyle-audits Winde\u2019s cabinet to undergo lifestyle audits], ''Mail & Guardian'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde confirmed on 3 June 2019 that a provincial children's commissioner would be appointed before the end of 2019 or in early 2020. He added that the commissioner would have the authority to monitor, investigate, research, lobby and educate on issues, policy, services and legislation that affect children.<ref>Kahla, Cheryl. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/child-protection-week-western-cape-to-childrens-commissioner-2019/ Child Protection Week: Western Cape to appoint children\u2019s commissioner], ''The South African'', 3 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref><ref>Petersen, Tammy. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/child-murder-capital-to-introduce-first-childrens-commissioner-20190610 Child murder capital to introduce first Children\u2019s Commissioner], ''News24'', 10 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref> In March 2020, the provincial parliament recommended rights activist Christina Nomdo for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tembo |first1=Theolin |title=Legislature paves way to appoint Christina Nomdo as Western Cape Commissioner of Children |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/legislature-paves-way-to-appoint-christina-nomdo-as-western-cape-commissioner-of-children-45202798 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 March 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nNational Police Minister [[Bheki Cele]] announced on 11 July 2019, that the [[South African National Defence Force]] (SANDF) would be deployed in the gang-ridden areas of [[Cape Town]]. Winde welcomed the deployment of SANDF. His predecessor, [[Helen Zille]], had repeatedly asked for the deployment of SANDF during her tenure. The deployment came into effect on 18 July 2019 and was set to end on 16 September 2019. However, Winde wrote to President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] and Defence Minister [[Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula]] in mid-September 2019 to request that the SANDF deployment in [[Cape Town]] be extended.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sandfs-deployment-to-cape-flats-cabinet-to-assess-situation-after-premier-winde-calls-for-an-extension-20190910 SANDF's deployment to Cape Flats: Cabinet to 'assess situation' after Premier Winde calls for an extension], ''News24'', 10 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> Winde reasoned that an extension of the army is required to bring stability to the communities.<ref>Etheridge, Jenna. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/still-a-massive-hill-to-climb-windes-reasons-for-wanting-army-to-stay-extra-6-months-20190911 'Still a massive hill to climb' - Winde's reasons for wanting army to stay extra 6 months], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> The cabinet granted the request and is now set to end in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-fritz-welcome-sandfs-extended-stay-but-want-to-see-a-few-changes-20190916 Winde, Fritz welcome SANDF's extended stay, but want to see a few changes], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-sandfs-deployment-in-western-cape-extended-to-march-2020-20190916 SANDF's deployment in Western Cape extended to March 2020], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde delivered his maiden [[State of the Province Address (South Africa)|State of the Province Address]] on 18 July 2019, in which he highlighted the provincial government's achievements and outlined his agenda.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/07/18/job-creation-gangs-likely-to-feature-in-premier-winde-s-sopa Job creation, gangs likely to feature in Premier Winde's Sopa], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 17 August 2019.</ref> Also in the speech, Winde placed emphasis on the [[Crime in South Africa|provincial crime and misconduct statistics]] and claimed that the police \"had lost the war on crime\" because of [[South African Police Service#Criticism and controversies|mismanagement]].<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2156487/police-have-lost-the-war-on-crime-in-the-western-cape-says-winde/ Police have lost the war on crime in the Western Cape, says Winde], ''The Citizen'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-govt-mulling-court-action-over-control-of-saps-in-province-20190718 Western Cape govt mulling court action over control of SAPS in province], ''News24'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2019, he appointed Harry Malila as the new Director-General of the Western Cape Provincial Government. Malila succeeded long-serving Brent Gerber.<ref>{{cite news |title=WATCH: Harry Malila appointed as Western Cape director-general |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-harry-malila-appointed-as-western-cape-director-general-35615157 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=22 October 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020, Winde delivered his second State of the Province Address at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]]. It was the first time that the SOPA was held outside of the Provincial Parliament's chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gitahu |first1=Mwangi |title=Focus on Western Cape Sopa at Mitchells Plain centre |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/focus-on-western-cape-sopa-at-mitchells-plain-centre-43010777 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and record==\n===Immigration===\nWinde had been critical of controversial immigration regulations introduced by the national government, which he alleged had harmed tourism growth in the Western Cape. In response, he organised petitions against the regulations.<ref>[https://www.nwivisas.com/nwi-blog/south-africa/mec-alan-winde-plans-to-petition-visa-regulations/ MEC Alan Winde plans to petition visa regulations], ''nwvisas''. Retrieved on 7 April 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.vocfm.co.za/regulations-detrimental-to-economy-winde/ Regulations detrimental to economy: Winde], ''Voice of the Cape'', 3 September 2014. Retrieved on 3 July 2019.</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nProvincial government officials visited clothing factories in the Cape Town area on 11 June 2012. Winde investigated a local government leadership programme. The specific programme aimed to give the unemployed youth work experience.<ref>Adams, Nathan. [https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/11/Winde-visits-clothing-factories Winde visits clothing factories], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 June 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde approached the [[Development Bank of South Africa]] on 31 July 2012 to secure funding for the provincial government's work and skill programme. The programme has been active since 2009. Winde announced that if the provincial government could acquire additional funding, an extra 600 young people would be able to benefit from this project.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2012/07/31/WC-Skills-programme-needs-funding WC skills programme needs funding], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 July 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe visited small businesses in the Cape Town CBD on 15 January 2013. He called on the businesses to enter the province's Entrepreneurship Recognition Awards.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/01/15/Winde-promotes-Entrepreneurship-Awards Winde promotes Entrepreneurship Awards], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 15 January 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Western Cape Economic Development Department launched an artisan development programme on 20 August 2013 to train more artisans. Winde said that his department would be putting special focus on crucial industries in the province.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/08/20/Qualified-artisans-have-become-scarce 'Qualified artisans are scarce'], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 August 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Premier Helen Zille led a delegation to China in November 2015 in a bid to secure increased trade and investment opportunities. A report from 2013 estimated that the province's exports to China were valued at over [[South African rand|R]]2 billion (US$131.8 million).<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/11/13/Zille-Winde-lead-delegation-to-China Zille, Winde to lead delegation to China], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 13 November 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe said on 10 October 2018 that youth unemployment should be the main focus of the national job and employment summit, hosted by the [[Government of South Africa|national government]]. The Provincial Department of Economic Development has initiated many employment projects aiming to employ the unemployed youth.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/04/job-summit-can-t-be-allowed-to-become-another-talk-shop Youth unemployment must be key focus of job summit - Alan Winde], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 4 October 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde has been commended for creating a business-friendly environment in the Western Cape since the provincial economy has performed better than the national growth rate.<ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> The Western Cape currently has a lower unemployment rate compared to the national average. Democratic Alliance Federal Leader [[Mmusi Maimane]] called Winde the \"premier of jobs\", when he announced him as the party's candidate.<ref>Mpahlele, Mary Jane. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-premier-candidate-alan-winde-to-focus-on-job-creation-housing-17144485 DA Premier candidate Alan Winde to focus on job creation, housing], ''IOL'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He has even received praise for his economic policies from senior opposition politicians. Deputy President of South Africa and senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] figure [[David Mabuza]] said in September 2019 that the provincial government's economic policies should be implemented in other ANC-run provinces.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-09-11-da-premier-alan-winde-gets-surprise-endorsement-from-david-mabuza/ DA premier Alan Winde gets surprise endorsement from David Mabuza], ''TimesLIVE'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019</ref><ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/mabuza-praises-winde-as-a-good-selection-says-plans-are-afoot-to-settle-people-in-the-western-cape-20190911 Mabuza praises Winde as a 'good selection', says plans are afoot to settle people in the Western Cape], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political infighting and corruption===\nDemocratic Alliance party insiders have described Winde as someone who is not involved in party infighting and prioritised on completing his work.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. \n [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 7 April 2019. \"Winde is largely seen within the party as someone who is focused on his job and does not get involved in political infighting.\"</ref>\n\nDuring his premiership, Winde has strongly opposed corruption. He made it mandatory for his provincial ministers to undergo lifestyle audits. He announced in August 2019 that he would probe all the corruption allegations made against his provincial ministers. He made this announcement after the official opposition [[African National Congress]] had called for an investigation into alleged misconduct by the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Winde vows to probe all corruption allegation against MECs |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/30/winde-vows-to-probe-all-corruption-allegation-against-mecs | newspaper=EWN|accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nFollowing Winde's deployment to the Community Safety Department in November 2018, he announced that revised technology would be used to prevent and reduce crime. In the same month, he met with Hanover Park Peace Ambassador, Riedwaan Samuels, who was shot four times in the leg. Winde praised all the young peace ambassadors who were standing up against gang violence and fighting for their communities to be safer. He also met with Western Cape Police Commissioner, Khombinkosi Jula, and discussed that the addition of new police officers would help with the police under-resourcing in the Western Cape.<ref>Maliti, Soyiso. [https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/news/windes-plan-to-fight-crime-using-tech-17759673 Winde's plan to fight crime using tech], ''IOL'', 3 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Mlamla, Sisonke. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/pics-praise-for-hanover-park-peace-ambassador-who-was-shot-17791173 PICS: Praise for Hanover Park Peace Ambassador who was shot], ''IOL'', 6 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/11/09/wc-police-service-boosted-by-addition-of-1-000-new-recruits WC police service boosted by addition of 1,000 new recruits], ''EWN'', 9 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Winde called for the establishment of a provincial police force. In mid-December, [[Philippi, Cape Town|Philippi]] farmers requested that the Provincial Community Safety Department allocate more police officers to the area. In response, the Provincial Community Safety Department wrote a letter to the Western Cape Police Commissioner.<ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-wants-provincial-police-force-for-western-cape-20181213 Winde wants provincial police force for Western Cape], ''News24'', 13 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/12/18/philippi-urge-mec-alan-winde-to-urgently-allocate-them-more-police Philippi farmers urge MEC Winde to urgently allocate them more police], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government formally declared an inter-governmental dispute with National Minister of Police [[Bheki Cele]] on 29 April 2019 over police resources allocated to the province.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-04-28-western-cape-government-declares-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-policing/ Western Cape government declares dispute with Bheki Cele over policing], ''TimesLIVE'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/crime/2123896/western-cape-government-declares-formal-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-police-resourcing-da/ Western Cape government declares formal dispute with Bheki Cele over police resourcing \u2013 DA], ''TheCitizen'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref>\n\nSANDF was deployed to the areas of [[Cape Town]] affected by high levels of crime and gang violence in July 2019. Winde welcomed the decision by the [[Department of Defence (South Africa)|National Department of Defence]] to assist the police in its efforts to reduce the city's crime statistics.<ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/go-in-arrest-those-gangsters-w-cape-premier-on-military-move-20190711 Go in, arrest those gangsters: W Cape premier on military move], ''News24'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref><ref>Mabuza, Ernest. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-11-police-minister-bheki-cele-deploys-army-to-crime-ridden-western-cape/ Police minister Bheki Cele deploys army to crime-ridden Western Cape], ''BusinessDay'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref> The deployment was extended in September 2019.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/winde-welcomes-sandf-extension-but-wants-criminal-justice-system-fixed-33080728 Winde welcomes SANDF extension but wants criminal justice system fixed], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Provincial Minister of Community Safety [[Albert Fritz]] announced on 19 September 2019 that the provincial government would annually be investing R1 billion (US$67.3 million) for three years into the training and deployment of 3,000 safety officers and 150 investigators. A total of 500 safety officers were deployed in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC provincial police service set to be deployed in February |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/05/wc-provincial-police-service-set-to-be-deployed-in-february |accessdate=14 December 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=500 new law enforcement officers deployed to crime hot spots in Cape Town |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/500-new-law-enforcement-officers-deployed-to-crime-hot-spots-in-cape-town-20200210 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The safety plan aims to halve the province's crime statistics within the next decade. Fritz added that the provincial government would also establish an integrated violence prevention programme. The provincial ministers would also be assessed by key performance indicators (KPIs) related to the safety plan.<ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/windes-r1bn-safety-plan-3-000-new-law-enforcement-officers-150-investigators-20190919 Winde's R1bn safety plan: 3 000 new law enforcement officers, 150 investigators], ''News24'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>Buhle, Lindwa. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/premier-winde-announces-western-cape-most-expensive-safety-plan/ Western Cape\u2019s crime-fighting plan: R1-billion, 3000 new officers and more], ''The South African'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.702.co.za/articles/361338/winde-to-appoint-3000-new-officers-in-three-year-wc-safety-plan Winde to appoint 3000 new officers in three-year WC safety plan], ''www.702.co.za'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Agriculture and tourism===\nOne of his duties, as Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities, was to oversee the Tourism Department of the Western Cape Government. He was responsible for projects such as Project Khulisa, a project introduced by the provincial government to increase tourism growth and grow the South African economy. The project resulted in the Western Cape tourism sector growing extensively.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/09/01/WC-Govt-launch-economic-growth-plan WC govt launches economic growth plan], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 1 September 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced that it was investing more than R23 million (US$1.5 million) on increasing the province's agricultural exports and set a target of creating 100,000 jobs in the sector. Winde said that additional support would be given to emerging farmers.<ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/30/WC-govt-invests-over-R23m-on-increasing-agricultural-exports WC govt invests over R23m on increasing agricultural exports], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/31/WC-govt-to-create-more-than-100-thousand-jobs-in-agricultural-sector WC to create over 100,000 jobs in agricultural sector], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Cape Town water crisis|drought]] that ravaged the Western Cape province from 2017 to 2018, he argued for farmers to keep hold of their private agricultural water supply, even if their local municipalities had a shortage of water.<ref>Head, Tom. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-alan-winde-western-cape-premier/ Breaking: Alan Winde revealed as the DA\u2019s choice for Western Cape premier], ''The South African'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nDuring a campaign visit to the West Coast region of the Western Cape province on 8 January 2019, Winde urged communities to protect infrastructure. He made this announcement after he witnessed fire-damaged municipal buildings in the town of [[Saldanha Bay]]. The buildings were set on fire during violent protests that occurred in 2018.<ref>Brandt, Kevin. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/01/08/da-wc-premier-candidate-winde-embarks-door-to-door-campaign Winde urges communities to protect infrastructure during door-to-door campaign], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 8 January 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Electricity===\nWinde called for the Western Cape to draw its electricity from natural resources and be independent of [[Eskom|Eskom's]] electricity supply in March 2019.<ref>Mokone, Thabo. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-03-02-da-wants-western-cape-off-eskom-grid/ DA wants Western Cape off Eskom grid], ''TimesLIVE'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref> He said that it is his ambition for the City of Cape Town to become the first city in South Africa to procure electricity from independent suppliers.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/20/alan-winde-says-eskom-crisis-will-cripple-sa-s-economy DA's Winde hopes CT can be the first to get power from independent suppliers], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[Eskom]] announced another round of [[2007\u20132019 South African energy crisis|power outages]]. Winde described the announcement as the \"last straw\" and called on Minister of Energy [[Gwede Mantashe]] to consider a proposal in which municipalities obtain electricity directly from IPPs.<ref>Mabuza, Ernst. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-10-17-alan-winde-asks-gwede-mantashe-to-allow-municipalities-to-procure-clean-energy/ Alan Winde asks Gwede Mantashe to allow municipalities to procure clean energy], ''TimesLIVE'', 17 October 2019. Retrieved on 17 October 2019.</ref> Mantashe, later on, agreed to discuss the matter.<ref>Meyer, Dan. [https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-11-19-gwede-mantashe-opens-a-gap-will-discuss-independent-power-for-western-cape/ Gwede Mantashe opens a gap - will 'discuss' independent power for Western Cape], ''SowetanLIVE'', 19 November 2019. Retrieved on 6 December 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, President Ramaphosa announced in his State of the Nation Address that municipalities with an adequate financial standing would be allowed to purchase electricity from IPPs. Winde welcomed the decision and called for it to be expedited.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brandt |first1=Kevin |title=WC Premier Winde looking to quickly implement Ramaphosa's IPP announcement |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/02/14/wc-premier-winde-looking-to-quickly-implement-ramaphosa-s-ipp-announcement-1 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alan Winde}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/alan-winde/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/profile/mr-alan-winde Provincial Minister of Community Safety]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/97 Premier of the Western Cape: Overview]\n* [https://cfo.co.za/article/alan-winde Profile: Alan Winde] at CFO South Africa\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/alan-winde Alan Winde, Mr] at [[Government of South Africa]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Helen Zille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Plato]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fritz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=''Position established''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Garth Strachan}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Position dissolved''}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{WCPremiers}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winde, Alan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from Knysna]]\n[[Category:South African businesspeople]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:Premiers of the Western Cape]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Alan Winde\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image               = Alan Winde.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Winde in 2018\n| office              = 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]\n| status              = \n| premier             = \n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Helen Zille]]\n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]\n| premier1            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1         = 1 November 2018\n| term_end1           = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Dan Plato]]\n| successor1          = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office2             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]\n| premier2            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2         = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2           = 1 November 2018\n| alongside2          = \n| constituency2       = \n| predecessor2        = ''Position established''\n| successor2          = [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] \n| majority2           = \n| prior_term2         =\n| office3             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]\n| premier3            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2009\n| term_end3           = 26 May 2014\n| alongside3          = \n| constituency3       = \n| predecessor3        = Garth Strachan\n| successor3          = ''Position dissolved''\n| majority3           = \n| prior_term3         =\n| office4            = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start4        = 15 June 1999\n| birthname          = Alan Richard Winde\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knysna]], [[Cape Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = [[South Africa]]n\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (1999\u20132000) <br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (Before 1999)\n| spouse             = Tracy Winde (m. 1993)\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = 2\n| residence          = [[Knysna]]<br />[[Cape Town]]\n| education          = Knysna High School\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician<br />Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Alan Richard Winde''' (born 18 March 1965) is a South African politician and previous businessman.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', Western Cape, 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 30 September 2018.</ref> He is currently serving as the 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]] since his election in 2019, and a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] since 1999. He previously served as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]], the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]] and the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]. Winde is a member of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA).\n\nBorn in [[Knysna]], Winde attended Knysna High School. He has experience as a businessman and entrepreneur since he established several businesses. He also worked for and managed numerous companies. He started his political career as a municipal and district councillor in the early 1990s. Shortly afterwards in 1999, he was elected to the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He has held various leadership positions in the Democratic Alliance provincial parliament caucus. Winde was appointed [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]] in May 2009 and served until May 2014, when he assumed the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet], ''Mail & Guardian''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref><ref>Williams, Murray. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the Democratic Alliance selected Winde to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-named-da-candidate-to-take-over-from-helen-zille-as-premier/ Alan Winde named DA candidate to take over from Helen Zille as premier], ''TimesLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref> In October 2018, Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed Winde to the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]. He took office on 1 November 2018.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the Democratic Alliance retained their majority in the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]], but with a decrease in the number of seats.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-10-democratic-alliance-officially-wins-the-western-cape-vote/ It's official: The Democratic Alliance has won the Western Cape], ''TimesLIVE'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> Winde was elected Premier on 22 May 2019 and succeeded Helen Zille. He is the second Western Cape Premier from the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Le Roux |first1=Nckey |title=Winde formally elected as Premier on 22 May |url=https://www.georgeherald.com/News/Article/Elections-2019/premier-elect-inaugurated-on-22-may-201905131129 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=George Herald |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and business career==\n===Family and personal life===\nWinde was born on 18 March 1965 in the town of [[Knysna]]. He attended and matriculated from Knysna High School. He married Tracy Winde in 1993. They have two children named Lauren and Jason.<ref name = \"onesaforall\">[https://www.onesouthafricaforall.co.za/ Alan Winde], ''Democratic Alliance''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde's father, William Dave Winde, died on 1 August 2019.<ref>(In Afrikaans) [https://www.son.co.za/Nuus/Suid-Kaap/premier-se-pa-oorlede-20190801 Winde se pa oorlede], ''Son Digitaal'', 1 August 2019. Retrieved on 1 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===Business career===\nWinde has experience as an entrepreneur. He established and managed many small businesses. He was also a director of a tour company and a business broker with Aldes Business Brokers.<ref name=\"onesaforall\" />\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Minister Alan Winde (cropped).jpg|x200px|thumb|left|Winde as Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism in 2013]]\nWinde ran as an independent candidate and was elected to the South Cape District Council in 1996. He had previously served as a councillor for the Outeniqua Rural Council. Shortly after being elected a district councillor, the [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] recruited him to be a candidate for the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He was elected in the [[1999 South African general election|general election of 1999]].<ref name =\"bizzabo\">[https://events.bizzabo.com/u-start-conference-africa/agenda/speakers/89264 Alan Winde - Bizzabo], ''U-Start Conference Africa''. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe took office as a Member on 15 June 2009. During his first term, he served as Western Cape Provincial Finance Chairman and a Member of the Executive Committee. He returned to the Provincial Parliament following the 2004 general election. Briefly, before being re-elected in 2009, he served as Chief Whip of the Official Opposition, Party Spokesperson on Environment and Planning and Deputy Party Spokesperson on Economic Development and Tourism.<ref name=\"bizzabo\" />\n\nPremier Helen Zille appointed Winde to the position of Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism following his re-election in May 2009. Constitutional Court Judge [[Yvonne Mokgoro]] swore him in as Provincial Minister on 7 May 2009. He consequently succeeded Garth Strachan.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/appointment-western-cape-provincial-cabinet Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 7 May 2009. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the 2014 elections, Premier Helen Zille announced that Winde would now hold the title of Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities and only lead the Provincial Departments of Agriculture, Economic Development and Tourism. The Provincial Finance Department would be an independent department with its own Provincial Minister. Western Cape Deputy Judge President Jeanette Traverso swore him in on 26 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/premier-helen-zille-announces-new-cabinet Premier Helen Zille Announces New Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Winde was selected by the DA's Federal Executive to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate for the 2019 provincial election.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-da-names-alan-winde-western-cape-premier-candidate WATCH: DA names Alan Winde as Western Cape Premier candidate], ''eNCA'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPremier Helen Zille announced in October 2018 that Winde would move to the Provincial Community Safety Department as incumbent Provincial Minister [[Dan Plato]] had announced his intention to resign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thaw |first1=Regan |title=Alan Winde to take over WC Community Safety portfolio |url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=19 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |archivedate=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alan Winde replacing Dan Plato as community safety MEC |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/alan-winde-replacing-dan-plato-as-community-safety-mec-17553379 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> Winde was succeeded by [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] on 1 November 2018. He subsequently assumed the post of Provincial Minister of Community Safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=Western Cape Economic Development on swearing in of MEC Beverley Sch\u00e4fer |url=https://www.gov.za/speeches/western-cape-economic-development-swearing-mec-beverley-sch%C3%A4fer-1-nov-2018-0000 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |publisher=South African Government |date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nWinde has served as acting Premier of the Western Cape on various brief occasions.<ref>[https://twitter.com/alanwinde/status/1092696090162446337 Alan Winde on Twitter: \"I have just been sworn in as Acting Premier. I agreed with the Judge not to invade any neighboring country.\"]. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He represented the provincial government at the [[State of the Nation Address (South Africa)|February 2019 State of the Nation Address]], as [[Helen Zille]] was in [[Germany]].<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sona-2019-from-thuma-mina-to-new-dawn-fades-as-bosasa-casts-a-shadow-20190208 SONA 2019: From 'Thuma Mina' to 'New Dawn Fades' as Bosasa casts a shadow], News24, 8 February 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n== Premier of the Western Cape (2019\u2013present)==\n===Campaign===\n{{see also|2019 Western Cape provincial election}}\n[[File:Alan Winde For Premier Campaign Bus 2019 (cropped).jpg|270px|thumb|Alan Winde for Premier campaign bus, which was unveiled in April 2019.]]\nWinde emerged as the front-runner quite early on in the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=Who wants to be the Western Cape's next |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/who-wants-to-be-the-western-capes-next-premier-15527764 |accessdate=28 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=18 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, Democratic Alliance Federal Leader, [[Mmusi Maimane]], announced Winde as the party's Western Cape Premier candidate to succeed Premier [[Helen Zille]] after the 2019 elections. Winde defeated prominent candidates such as the Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape, [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]], and Member of Parliament [[David Maynier]]. After the announcement, Madikizela endorsed Winde and offered his full support to Winde's campaign.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', [[Western Cape]], 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Dentlinger, Lindsay. [https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/featured/da-wc-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-backs-alan-winde-as-premier-candidate/ar-BBNA1TB DA WC leader Bonginkosi Madikizela backs Alan Winde as premier candidate], ''MSN'', 20 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance launched their campaign to retain the Western Cape after the 2019 elections at the [[Cape Town Stadium]] on 29 September 2018. At the event, Mmusi Maimane highlighted the party's achievements while governing the province, such as the province's low unemployment rate and that the party had turned the previously struggling Provincial Education Department into one of the best functioning departments in South Africa.<ref>Isaacs, Lauren. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/30/da-determined-to-retain-western-cape-in-2019-elections DA determined to retain Western Cape in 2019 elections],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/unity-the-rallying-call-for-western-cape-da-as-it-launches-its-election-campaign-20180929 Unity the rallying call for Western Cape DA, as it launches its election campaign], ''News24'', 29 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter he was announced as the premier candidate, Winde embarked on a listening tour and travelled to various communities in the [[Western Cape]].<ref>[https://pr.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-DA-Western-Cape-Premier-Candidate-Winde-takes-Listening-Tour-to-George-8001073 #WindeForPremier: DA Western Cape Premier Candidate Winde takes Listening Tour to George], ''African News Agency'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nHe also campaigned for local DA candidates in by-elections. For instance, he went to the community of De Doorns to campaign for a DA candidate in a hotly-contested by-election. The DA candidate, Luwellyn Willemse, retained ward 3 of the [[Breede Valley Local Municipality|Breede Valley municipality]] by earning a total of 1,101 votes (52.16%).<ref>{{cite news |title=DA retains ward in Breede Valley municipal by-election |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2027939/da-retains-ward-in-breede-valley-municipal-by-election/ |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-Alan-Winde-to-address-supporters-at-De-Doorns-final-rally-ahead-of-by-election-7777913 #WindeForPremier: Alan Winde to address supporters at De Doorns final rally ahead of by-election], ''African News Agency''. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde launched the Democratic Alliance's 2019 provincial voter registration campaign on 4 January 2019. Winde and other Democratic Alliance members erected party registration posters in [[Mitchells Plain]], ahead of the Independent Electoral Commission's registration weekend on 26 and 27 January 2019.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-winde-launches-das-campaign-voter-registration-plan-criticised-18686993 WATCH: Winde launches DA's campaign, voter registration plan criticised], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 5 August 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance held its provincial Plan of Action Rally on 2 March 2019 at the [[Bellville Velodrome]] and launched their provincial party manifesto. Winde and various other DA politicians addressed thousands of party supporters. Winde assured that he would take on the national government for the Western Cape to receive its own, decentralised [[Rail transport in South Africa|rail]] and [[South African Police Service|police service]]. He pledged to increase the availability of [[Housing voucher|housing vouchers]] and vowed to spend [[Taxation in South Africa|tax money]] properly.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/da-comes-out-guns-blazing-to-retain-control-of-wc DA comes out guns blazing to retain control of WC], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref><ref>Payne, Sune. [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-03-04-da-punts-control-of-rail-and-policing-in-western-cape-as-party-launches-provincial-manifesto/ DA punts control of rail and policing in Western Cape as party launches provincial manifesto], ''The Daily Maverick'', 4 March 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref><ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/maimane-unemployment-will-continue-to-rise-the-longer-anc-stays-in-power Maimane: Unemployment will continue to rise the longer ANC stays in power],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde vowed on 11 March 2019 to build a police station in the gang-riddled community of [[Bonteheuwel]] due to the large number of murders that occur in the suburb.<ref>Mortlock, Monique.  \n[https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/11/winde-promises-to-a-police-station-in-bonteheuwel-if-da-wins-elections Winde promises to build police station in Bonteheuwel if DA wins elections], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde participated in the first [[eNCA]] Town Hall Debate, hosted at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]] on 14 March 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-emotions-run-high-encas-town-hall-debate WATCH: Emotions run high at eNCA's Town Hall Debate], ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref> The debate included many senior Western Cape politicians, such as former African National Congress Premier, [[Ebrahim Rasool]], Economic Freedom Fighters City of Cape Town councillor, [[Melikhaya Xego]], Good Party Leader, [[Patricia de Lille]], and Freedom Front Plus Western Cape Premier candidate, [[Peter Marais]].<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/senior-politicians-trade-barbs-campaign-at-enca-townhall-debate-in-the-capes-mitchells-plain-20190314 Senior politicians trade barbs, campaign at eNCA townhall debate in the Cape's Mitchells Plain], ''News24'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/live-video-cape-town-pre-election-town-hall-meetings WATCH: eNCA Town Hall Debate - Cape Town], Johannesburg, ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019.  Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and [[Mmusi Maimane]] revealed the Democratic Alliance's alternative energy plan for the Western Cape on 27 March 2019, in which the province acquires electricity directly from Independent Power Producers (IPPs).<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-maimane-winde-reveal-das-alternative-energy-plan-20115500 WATCH: Maimane, Winde reveal DA's alternative energy plan], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 27 March 2019. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance retained control of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, but with a decrease in the number of seats, on 8 May 2019.<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/elections/2128368/live-da-secures-majority-again-in-western-cape-election-results/ LIVE: DA secures majority again in Western Cape election results], ''The Citizen'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> The party celebrated their election win in the province on 16 May 2019.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/campaigning-a-reality-check-das-winde-admits-as-he-thanks-the-western-cape-20190516 Campaigning a 'reality check', DA's Winde admits as he thanks the Western Cape], ''News24'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved on 18 May 2019.</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWinde was elected Premier of the Western Cape on 22 May 2019 during the first sitting of the Sixth Provincial Parliament. He received 24 out of the 34 valid votes. Six ballots were spoilt, and there were two abstentions. His main challenger for the post was [[Cameron Dugmore]] of the [[African National Congress]], who received only 10 out of the 34 valid votes.<ref>Lee, Samantha. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Peoples-Post/breaking-winde-sworn-in-as-western-cape-premier-20190522 Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''News24'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>Mortlock, Monique. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/da-s-winde-elected-as-new-wc-premier DA's Winde elected as new WC premier], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2133822/winde-elected-western-cape-premier/ Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''The Citizen'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde announced the formation of his Provincial Cabinet on 23 May 2019. He retained four ministers in their existing portfolios, while he moved three to other portfolios and appointed three new members. He appointed former DA Member of Parliament and premier candidate contender, [[David Maynier]], to the post of Provincial Minister of Finance and Economic Opportunities, while he moved [[Albert Fritz]] and [[Ivan Meyer]] to the posts of Provincial Minister of Community Safety and Provincial Minister of Agriculture, respectively. Winde also said that all the newly-appointed cabinet members would undergo lifestyle audits.<ref name=\"provincial cabinet\">\n*Sicetsha, Andile. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/western-cape-premier-alan-winde-new-cabinet/ Western Cape Premier Alan Winde announces new Cabinet], ''The South African'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 9 September 2019.\n*Meyer, Dan. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new], ''TimesLVE'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.\n*[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-names-western-cape-cabinet-20190523 Winde names new Western Cape cabinet], ''News24'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Nkanjeni, Unathi. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-24-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-western-cape-provincial-cabinet/ What you need to know about the Western Cape provincial cabinet], ''TimesLIVE'', 24 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Kiewit, Lester. [https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-23-windes-cabinet-to-undergo-lifestyle-audits Winde\u2019s cabinet to undergo lifestyle audits], ''Mail & Guardian'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde confirmed on 3 June 2019 that a provincial children's commissioner would be appointed before the end of 2019 or in early 2020. He added that the commissioner would have the authority to monitor, investigate, research, lobby and educate on issues, policy, services and legislation that affect children.<ref>Kahla, Cheryl. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/child-protection-week-western-cape-to-childrens-commissioner-2019/ Child Protection Week: Western Cape to appoint children\u2019s commissioner], ''The South African'', 3 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref><ref>Petersen, Tammy. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/child-murder-capital-to-introduce-first-childrens-commissioner-20190610 Child murder capital to introduce first Children\u2019s Commissioner], ''News24'', 10 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref> In March 2020, the provincial parliament recommended rights activist Christina Nomdo for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tembo |first1=Theolin |title=Legislature paves way to appoint Christina Nomdo as Western Cape Commissioner of Children |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/legislature-paves-way-to-appoint-christina-nomdo-as-western-cape-commissioner-of-children-45202798 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 March 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nNational Police Minister [[Bheki Cele]] announced on 11 July 2019, that the [[South African National Defence Force]] (SANDF) would be deployed in the gang-ridden areas of [[Cape Town]]. Winde welcomed the deployment of SANDF. His predecessor, [[Helen Zille]], had repeatedly asked for the deployment of SANDF during her tenure. The deployment came into effect on 18 July 2019 and was set to end on 16 September 2019. However, Winde wrote to President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] and Defence Minister [[Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula]] in mid-September 2019 to request that the SANDF deployment in [[Cape Town]] be extended.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sandfs-deployment-to-cape-flats-cabinet-to-assess-situation-after-premier-winde-calls-for-an-extension-20190910 SANDF's deployment to Cape Flats: Cabinet to 'assess situation' after Premier Winde calls for an extension], ''News24'', 10 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> Winde reasoned that an extension of the army is required to bring stability to the communities.<ref>Etheridge, Jenna. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/still-a-massive-hill-to-climb-windes-reasons-for-wanting-army-to-stay-extra-6-months-20190911 'Still a massive hill to climb' - Winde's reasons for wanting army to stay extra 6 months], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> The cabinet granted the request and is now set to end in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-fritz-welcome-sandfs-extended-stay-but-want-to-see-a-few-changes-20190916 Winde, Fritz welcome SANDF's extended stay, but want to see a few changes], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-sandfs-deployment-in-western-cape-extended-to-march-2020-20190916 SANDF's deployment in Western Cape extended to March 2020], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde delivered his maiden [[State of the Province Address (South Africa)|State of the Province Address]] on 18 July 2019, in which he highlighted the provincial government's achievements and outlined his agenda.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/07/18/job-creation-gangs-likely-to-feature-in-premier-winde-s-sopa Job creation, gangs likely to feature in Premier Winde's Sopa], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 17 August 2019.</ref> Also in the speech, Winde placed emphasis on the [[Crime in South Africa|provincial crime and misconduct statistics]] and claimed that the police \"had lost the war on crime\" because of [[South African Police Service#Criticism and controversies|mismanagement]].<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2156487/police-have-lost-the-war-on-crime-in-the-western-cape-says-winde/ Police have lost the war on crime in the Western Cape, says Winde], ''The Citizen'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-govt-mulling-court-action-over-control-of-saps-in-province-20190718 Western Cape govt mulling court action over control of SAPS in province], ''News24'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2019, he appointed Harry Malila as the new Director-General of the Western Cape Provincial Government. Malila succeeded long-serving Brent Gerber.<ref>{{cite news |title=WATCH: Harry Malila appointed as Western Cape director-general |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-harry-malila-appointed-as-western-cape-director-general-35615157 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=22 October 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020, Winde delivered his second State of the Province Address at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]]. It was the first time that the SOPA was held outside of the Provincial Parliament's chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gitahu |first1=Mwangi |title=Focus on Western Cape Sopa at Mitchells Plain centre |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/focus-on-western-cape-sopa-at-mitchells-plain-centre-43010777 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and record==\n===Immigration===\nWinde had been critical of controversial immigration regulations introduced by the national government, which he alleged had harmed tourism growth in the Western Cape. In response, he organised petitions against the regulations.<ref>[https://www.nwivisas.com/nwi-blog/south-africa/mec-alan-winde-plans-to-petition-visa-regulations/ MEC Alan Winde plans to petition visa regulations], ''nwvisas''. Retrieved on 7 April 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.vocfm.co.za/regulations-detrimental-to-economy-winde/ Regulations detrimental to economy: Winde], ''Voice of the Cape'', 3 September 2014. Retrieved on 3 July 2019.</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nProvincial government officials visited clothing factories in the Cape Town area on 11 June 2012. Winde investigated a local government leadership programme. The specific programme aimed to give the unemployed youth work experience.<ref>Adams, Nathan. [https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/11/Winde-visits-clothing-factories Winde visits clothing factories], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 June 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde approached the [[Development Bank of South Africa]] on 31 July 2012 to secure funding for the provincial government's work and skill programme. The programme has been active since 2009. Winde announced that if the provincial government could acquire additional funding, an extra 600 young people would be able to benefit from this project.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2012/07/31/WC-Skills-programme-needs-funding WC skills programme needs funding], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 July 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe visited small businesses in the Cape Town CBD on 15 January 2013. He called on the businesses to enter the province's Entrepreneurship Recognition Awards.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/01/15/Winde-promotes-Entrepreneurship-Awards Winde promotes Entrepreneurship Awards], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 15 January 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Western Cape Economic Development Department launched an artisan development programme on 20 August 2013 to train more artisans. Winde said that his department would be putting special focus on crucial industries in the province.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/08/20/Qualified-artisans-have-become-scarce 'Qualified artisans are scarce'], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 August 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Premier Helen Zille led a delegation to China in November 2015 in a bid to secure increased trade and investment opportunities. A report from 2013 estimated that the province's exports to China were valued at over [[South African rand|R]]2 billion (US$131.8 million).<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/11/13/Zille-Winde-lead-delegation-to-China Zille, Winde to lead delegation to China], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 13 November 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe said on 10 October 2018 that youth unemployment should be the main focus of the national job and employment summit, hosted by the [[Government of South Africa|national government]]. The Provincial Department of Economic Development has initiated many employment projects aiming to employ the unemployed youth.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/04/job-summit-can-t-be-allowed-to-become-another-talk-shop Youth unemployment must be key focus of job summit - Alan Winde], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 4 October 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde has been commended for creating a business-friendly environment in the Western Cape since the provincial economy has performed better than the national growth rate.<ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> The Western Cape currently has a lower unemployment rate compared to the national average. Democratic Alliance Federal Leader [[Mmusi Maimane]] called Winde the \"premier of jobs\", when he announced him as the party's candidate.<ref>Mpahlele, Mary Jane. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-premier-candidate-alan-winde-to-focus-on-job-creation-housing-17144485 DA Premier candidate Alan Winde to focus on job creation, housing], ''IOL'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He has even received praise for his economic policies from senior opposition politicians. Deputy President of South Africa and senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] figure [[David Mabuza]] said in September 2019 that the provincial government's economic policies should be implemented in other ANC-run provinces.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-09-11-da-premier-alan-winde-gets-surprise-endorsement-from-david-mabuza/ DA premier Alan Winde gets surprise endorsement from David Mabuza], ''TimesLIVE'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019</ref><ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/mabuza-praises-winde-as-a-good-selection-says-plans-are-afoot-to-settle-people-in-the-western-cape-20190911 Mabuza praises Winde as a 'good selection', says plans are afoot to settle people in the Western Cape], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political infighting and corruption===\nDemocratic Alliance party insiders have described Winde as someone who is not involved in party infighting and prioritised on completing his work.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. \n [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 7 April 2019. \"Winde is largely seen within the party as someone who is focused on his job and does not get involved in political infighting.\"</ref>\n\nDuring his premiership, Winde has strongly opposed corruption. He made it mandatory for his provincial ministers to undergo lifestyle audits. He announced in August 2019 that he would probe all the corruption allegations made against his provincial ministers. He made this announcement after the official opposition [[African National Congress]] had called for an investigation into alleged misconduct by the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Winde vows to probe all corruption allegation against MECs |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/30/winde-vows-to-probe-all-corruption-allegation-against-mecs | newspaper=EWN|accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nFollowing Winde's deployment to the Community Safety Department in November 2018, he announced that revised technology would be used to prevent and reduce crime. In the same month, he met with Hanover Park Peace Ambassador, Riedwaan Samuels, who was shot four times in the leg. Winde praised all the young peace ambassadors who were standing up against gang violence and fighting for their communities to be safer. He also met with Western Cape Police Commissioner, Khombinkosi Jula, and discussed that the addition of new police officers would help with the police under-resourcing in the Western Cape.<ref>Maliti, Soyiso. [https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/news/windes-plan-to-fight-crime-using-tech-17759673 Winde's plan to fight crime using tech], ''IOL'', 3 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Mlamla, Sisonke. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/pics-praise-for-hanover-park-peace-ambassador-who-was-shot-17791173 PICS: Praise for Hanover Park Peace Ambassador who was shot], ''IOL'', 6 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/11/09/wc-police-service-boosted-by-addition-of-1-000-new-recruits WC police service boosted by addition of 1,000 new recruits], ''EWN'', 9 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Winde called for the establishment of a provincial police force. In mid-December, [[Philippi, Cape Town|Philippi]] farmers requested that the Provincial Community Safety Department allocate more police officers to the area. In response, the Provincial Community Safety Department wrote a letter to the Western Cape Police Commissioner.<ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-wants-provincial-police-force-for-western-cape-20181213 Winde wants provincial police force for Western Cape], ''News24'', 13 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/12/18/philippi-urge-mec-alan-winde-to-urgently-allocate-them-more-police Philippi farmers urge MEC Winde to urgently allocate them more police], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government formally declared an inter-governmental dispute with National Minister of Police [[Bheki Cele]] on 29 April 2019 over police resources allocated to the province.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-04-28-western-cape-government-declares-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-policing/ Western Cape government declares dispute with Bheki Cele over policing], ''TimesLIVE'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/crime/2123896/western-cape-government-declares-formal-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-police-resourcing-da/ Western Cape government declares formal dispute with Bheki Cele over police resourcing \u2013 DA], ''TheCitizen'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref>\n\nSANDF was deployed to the areas of [[Cape Town]] affected by high levels of crime and gang violence in July 2019. Winde welcomed the decision by the [[Department of Defence (South Africa)|National Department of Defence]] to assist the police in its efforts to reduce the city's crime statistics.<ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/go-in-arrest-those-gangsters-w-cape-premier-on-military-move-20190711 Go in, arrest those gangsters: W Cape premier on military move], ''News24'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref><ref>Mabuza, Ernest. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-11-police-minister-bheki-cele-deploys-army-to-crime-ridden-western-cape/ Police minister Bheki Cele deploys army to crime-ridden Western Cape], ''BusinessDay'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref> The deployment was extended in September 2019.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/winde-welcomes-sandf-extension-but-wants-criminal-justice-system-fixed-33080728 Winde welcomes SANDF extension but wants criminal justice system fixed], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Provincial Minister of Community Safety [[Albert Fritz]] announced on 19 September 2019 that the provincial government would annually be investing R1 billion (US$67.3 million) for three years into the training and deployment of 3,000 safety officers and 150 investigators. A total of 500 safety officers were deployed in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC provincial police service set to be deployed in February |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/05/wc-provincial-police-service-set-to-be-deployed-in-february |accessdate=14 December 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=500 new law enforcement officers deployed to crime hot spots in Cape Town |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/500-new-law-enforcement-officers-deployed-to-crime-hot-spots-in-cape-town-20200210 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The safety plan aims to halve the province's crime statistics within the next decade. Fritz added that the provincial government would also establish an integrated violence prevention programme. The provincial ministers would also be assessed by key performance indicators (KPIs) related to the safety plan.<ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/windes-r1bn-safety-plan-3-000-new-law-enforcement-officers-150-investigators-20190919 Winde's R1bn safety plan: 3 000 new law enforcement officers, 150 investigators], ''News24'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>Buhle, Lindwa. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/premier-winde-announces-western-cape-most-expensive-safety-plan/ Western Cape\u2019s crime-fighting plan: R1-billion, 3000 new officers and more], ''The South African'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.702.co.za/articles/361338/winde-to-appoint-3000-new-officers-in-three-year-wc-safety-plan Winde to appoint 3000 new officers in three-year WC safety plan], ''www.702.co.za'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Agriculture and tourism===\nOne of his duties, as Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities, was to oversee the Tourism Department of the Western Cape Government. He was responsible for projects such as Project Khulisa, a project introduced by the provincial government to increase tourism growth and grow the South African economy. The project resulted in the Western Cape tourism sector growing extensively.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/09/01/WC-Govt-launch-economic-growth-plan WC govt launches economic growth plan], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 1 September 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced that it was investing more than R23 million (US$1.5 million) on increasing the province's agricultural exports and set a target of creating 100,000 jobs in the sector. Winde said that additional support would be given to emerging farmers.<ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/30/WC-govt-invests-over-R23m-on-increasing-agricultural-exports WC govt invests over R23m on increasing agricultural exports], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/31/WC-govt-to-create-more-than-100-thousand-jobs-in-agricultural-sector WC to create over 100,000 jobs in agricultural sector], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Cape Town water crisis|drought]] that ravaged the Western Cape province from 2017 to 2018, he argued for farmers to keep hold of their private agricultural water supply, even if their local municipalities had a shortage of water.<ref>Head, Tom. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-alan-winde-western-cape-premier/ Breaking: Alan Winde revealed as the DA\u2019s choice for Western Cape premier], ''The South African'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nDuring a campaign visit to the West Coast region of the Western Cape province on 8 January 2019, Winde urged communities to protect infrastructure. He made this announcement after he witnessed fire-damaged municipal buildings in the town of [[Saldanha Bay]]. The buildings were set on fire during violent protests that occurred in 2018.<ref>Brandt, Kevin. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/01/08/da-wc-premier-candidate-winde-embarks-door-to-door-campaign Winde urges communities to protect infrastructure during door-to-door campaign], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 8 January 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Electricity===\nWinde called for the Western Cape to draw its electricity from natural resources and be independent of [[Eskom|Eskom's]] electricity supply in March 2019.<ref>Mokone, Thabo. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-03-02-da-wants-western-cape-off-eskom-grid/ DA wants Western Cape off Eskom grid], ''TimesLIVE'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref> He said that it is his ambition for the City of Cape Town to become the first city in South Africa to procure electricity from independent suppliers.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/20/alan-winde-says-eskom-crisis-will-cripple-sa-s-economy DA's Winde hopes CT can be the first to get power from independent suppliers], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[Eskom]] announced another round of [[2007\u20132019 South African energy crisis|power outages]]. Winde described the announcement as the \"last straw\" and called on Minister of Energy [[Gwede Mantashe]] to consider a proposal in which municipalities obtain electricity directly from IPPs.<ref>Mabuza, Ernst. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-10-17-alan-winde-asks-gwede-mantashe-to-allow-municipalities-to-procure-clean-energy/ Alan Winde asks Gwede Mantashe to allow municipalities to procure clean energy], ''TimesLIVE'', 17 October 2019. Retrieved on 17 October 2019.</ref> Mantashe, later on, agreed to discuss the matter.<ref>Meyer, Dan. [https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-11-19-gwede-mantashe-opens-a-gap-will-discuss-independent-power-for-western-cape/ Gwede Mantashe opens a gap - will 'discuss' independent power for Western Cape], ''SowetanLIVE'', 19 November 2019. Retrieved on 6 December 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, President Ramaphosa announced in his State of the Nation Address that municipalities with an adequate financial standing would be allowed to purchase electricity from IPPs. Winde welcomed the decision and called for it to be expedited.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brandt |first1=Kevin |title=WC Premier Winde looking to quickly implement Ramaphosa's IPP announcement |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/02/14/wc-premier-winde-looking-to-quickly-implement-ramaphosa-s-ipp-announcement-1 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alan Winde}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/alan-winde/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/profile/mr-alan-winde Provincial Minister of Community Safety]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/97 Premier of the Western Cape: Overview]\n* [https://cfo.co.za/article/alan-winde Profile: Alan Winde] at CFO South Africa\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/alan-winde Alan Winde, Mr] at [[Government of South Africa]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Helen Zille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Plato]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fritz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=''Position established''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Garth Strachan}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Position dissolved''}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{WCPremiers}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winde, Alan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from Knysna]]\n[[Category:South African businesspeople]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:Premiers of the Western Cape]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTenure:LIVE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Winde"}
{"title_page": "Interstate 80 in New Jersey", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Highway detail hatnote|Interstate 80}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state = NJ\n|type = I\n|route = 80\n|alternate_name = Christopher Columbus Highway\n|map = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=line|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|stroke-width=3}}\n|map_custom = yes\n|map_notes = I-80 highlighted in red\n|map_alt = A map of New Jersey showing major roads. I-80 runs east-west across the northern part of the state.\n|maint=[[New Jersey Department of Transportation|NJDOT]] and [[Delaware River Joint Toll Bridge Commission|DRJTBC]]\n|length_mi = 68.54\n|length_ref =<ref name=sld>{{cite web |author = [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]] |date = April 2014 |url = http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/refdata/sldiag/pdf/00000080__-.pdf |title = I-80 Straight Line Diagram |department = Roadway Information and Traffic Monitoring System Program |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation |access-date = March 17, 2020 }}</ref>\n|history = Established 1958<ref name=\"1957 map\" /><br />Completed in 1973<ref name=nyt7 />\n|direction_a = West\n|terminus_a = {{Jct|state=PA|I|80}} at [[Pennsylvania]] border in [[Hardwick Township, New Jersey|Hardwick Township]]\n|junction = {{plainlist|\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|US|46|NJ|94}} in [[Knowlton Township, New Jersey|Knowlton Township]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|US|206|NJ|183}} in [[Roxbury, New Jersey|Roxbury]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|15}} in [[Wharton, New Jersey|Wharton]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|I|287}} in [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|I|280|US|46}} in Parsippany-Troy Hills\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|US|46|NJ|23}} in [[Wayne, New Jersey|Wayne]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|19}} in [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|20}} in Paterson\n* {{jct|state=NJ|GSP}} in [[Saddle Brook, New Jersey|Saddle Brook]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|17}} in [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]]\n}}\n|direction_b = East\n|terminus_b = {{Jct|state=NJ|I|95|NJTP|}} in [[Teaneck, New Jersey|Teaneck]]\n|counties = [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren]], [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]], [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris]], [[Essex County, New Jersey|Essex]], [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen]]\n|previous_type = NJ\n|previous_route = 79\n|next_type = NJ\n|next_route = 81\n}}\n\n'''Interstate 80''' ('''I-80''') is a major [[Interstate Highway]] in the [[United States]], running from [[San Francisco]], California eastward to the [[New York City Metropolitan Area]]. In [[New Jersey]], I-80 runs for {{convert|68.54|mi|km}} from the [[Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge]] at the [[Pennsylvania]] state line to its eastern terminus at [[Interstate 95 in New Jersey|I-95]] in [[Teaneck, New Jersey|Teaneck]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]]. I-95 continues from the end of I-80 to the [[George Washington Bridge]] for access to [[New York City]]. The highway runs parallel to [[U.S. Route&nbsp;46]] (US&nbsp;46) through rural areas of [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren]] and [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]] counties before heading into more suburban surroundings in [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris County]]. As the road continues into [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic]] and Bergen counties, it heads into more urban areas. The [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]] (NJDOT) identifies I-80 within the state as the '''Christopher Columbus Highway'''.<ref name=sld />\n\nA freeway along the I-80 corridor had been planned in 1936 and again in 1955 to provide relief along US&nbsp;46 between the George Washington Bridge and the [[Delaware Water Gap]]. With the establishment of the Interstate Highway System, this planned freeway, which had been identified in some planning documents as the '''Bergen-Passaic Expressway''', would be incorporated into I-80. The freeway was built across New Jersey in various stages from the 1960s to 1973. The westernmost four miles in New Jersey was originally a rerouting of [[U.S. Route 611|US&nbsp;611]] when built; that route was later realigned back into Pennsylvania. In the 1990s, [[high-occupancy vehicle lane]]s had existed on a part of I-80 in Morris County but were opened to regular traffic due to under-use.\n\n== Route description ==\n=== Warren and Sussex counties ===\n[[File:2018-06-28 09 19 00 View east along Interstate 80 just west of Exit 1 within the Delaware Water Gap in Hardwick Township, Warren County, New Jersey.jpg|thumb|left|View east along I-80 just after entering New Jersey within the Delaware Water Gap National Recreation Area]]\nI-80 enters [[Hardwick Township, New Jersey|Hardwick Township]], [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren County]] from Pennsylvania on the [[Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge]] over the [[Delaware River]], maintained by the [[Delaware River Joint Toll Bridge Commission]] (DRJTBC).<ref name=sld /> In addition to carrying I-80, this bridge also carries the [[Appalachian Trail]] over the Delaware River.  From this point, the four-lane freeway heads south along the east bank of the river through the [[Delaware Water Gap]], immediately reaching a westbound exit and eastbound entrance for [[Old Mine Road]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm>{{google maps |url = https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=40.976,+-75.1354&daddr=I-80+and+I-95+teaneck,+nj&geocode=%3BFfGTbwId88WW-ykFM6iKN_fCiTF8GZRr5zPfyA&hl=en&mra=ls&sll=40.978732,-75.069923&sspn=0.054042,0.1684&ie=UTF8&t=h&z=10 |title = Overview of Interstate 80 in New Jersey |access-date = January 14, 2010 }}</ref> Now maintained by [[New Jersey Department of Transportation|NJDOT]], the road makes a sharp turn to the east and comes to a [[U-turn]] ramp in both directions that also has access to the Appalachian Trail.<ref name=sld /> NJDOT has proposed a controversial rock wall along the stretch to handle rock slides.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njherald.com/20180219/a-rock-fence-or-a-stone-wall|title=In Water Gap, a rock fence or a stone wall?|last=Scruton|first=Bruce A.|date=February 19, 2018|website=New Jersey Herald|language=en|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref> The highway heads south again and enters [[Knowlton Township, New Jersey|Knowlton Township]], where it comes to another set of U-turn ramps that also includes a [[weigh station]] in the eastbound direction. After turning southeast and leaving the Delaware Water Gap, the road has a westbound [[right-in/right-out]] for Hainesburg Road before crossing under the abandoned [[Lackawanna Cutoff]]. I-80 widens to six lanes and reaches a complex interchange with the western terminus of [[U.S. Route 46|US&nbsp;46]], [[New Jersey Route 94|Route&nbsp;94]], and Decatur Street in [[Columbia, New Jersey|Columbia]], where development near the route increases. After this interchange, the freeway turns east away from the Delaware River and crosses over [[Paulins Kill]] before it continues through wooded and hilly areas containing some farms, with the eastbound direction widening from three to four lanes and the highway median also widens. A [[scenic overlook]] of the Delaware Water Gap is located in the westbound direction while a [[rest area]] is located in the eastbound direction.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm />\n\n[[File:80Expy Knowlton.JPG|right|thumb|I-80 westbound in [[Knowlton Township, New Jersey|Knowlton Township]]|alt=One direction of a freeway running through woodland]]\n\nUpon crossing into [[Blairstown Township, New Jersey|Blairstown Township]], the eastbound direction narrows down to three lanes.<ref name=sld /> In [[Hope Township, New Jersey|Hope Township]], I-80 reaches an interchange with [[County Route 521 (New Jersey)|County Route&nbsp;521]] (CR&nbsp;521) that also provides access to [[County Route 519 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;519]] and the [[Land of Make Believe (amusement park)|Land of Make Believe]] amusement park.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The highway widens to eight lanes briefly after this interchange before narrowing to six lanes. In [[Frelinghuysen Township, New Jersey|Frelinghuysen Township]], the freeway carries four lanes eastbound and three lanes westbound. Upon coming into [[Allamuchy Township, New Jersey|Allamuchy Township]], I-80 has six lanes before gaining a fourth eastbound lane as it comes to the [[County Route 517 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;517]] exit.<ref name=sld /> This exit gives the highway access to [[Allamuchy Mountain State Park]].<ref name=gm /> Following this, the road runs through densely forested areas of Allamuchy Mountain State Park, coming to two pairs of rest areas with no facilities in both directions. The eastbound direction becomes three lanes again before the road passes through [[Byram Township, New Jersey|Byram Township]] in [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex County]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm />\n\n=== Morris and Essex counties ===\n[[File:I80easthopetownshipyuvrajr.JPG|left|thumb|I-80 eastbound in Hope Township]]\nUpon crossing the [[Musconetcong River]], I-80 enters [[Mount Olive Township, New Jersey|Mount Olive Township]] in [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris County]] and passes through more woodland with a narrower median. The road comes to a [[trumpet interchange]] with [[U.S. Route 206|US&nbsp;206]] and forms a [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with that route as it bypasses [[Netcong, New Jersey|Netcong]] to the south.  After turning southeast and passing near suburban business parks, the highway crosses over [[NJ Transit]]\u2019s [[Morristown Line]]/[[Montclair-Boonton Line]] and reaches a partial interchange with US&nbsp;46.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> This interchange has only a westbound exit and eastbound entrance. The freeway crosses a small corner of Netcong and Mount Olive Township again before continuing into [[Roxbury Township, New Jersey|Roxbury Township]], where it comes to a modified [[cloverleaf interchange]].<ref name=sld /> At this interchange, [[New Jersey Route 183|Route&nbsp;183]] heads north into Netcong and US&nbsp;206 splits from I-80 by heading south. The road continues through wooded areas containing some suburban development as it comes to the CR&nbsp;631 interchange, which also provides access to eastbound US&nbsp;46.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The road crosses the NJ Transit line again and parallels it a short distance to the north as it comes into [[Mount Arlington, New Jersey|Mount Arlington]] and reaches the Howard Boulevard exit, serving [[Mount Arlington station]].<ref name=sld /> I-80 continues back into Roxbury Township and comes to a westbound truck rest area with the eastbound one being abandoned.<ref name=sld /><ref name=njdot2>{{cite web |url = http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/refdata/traffic_orders/rest_stops/rt80.shtm |department= NJDOT Traffic Regulations |title = Traffic and Parking in Rest Areas: Interstate 80 |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=gsv>{{cite web |author = Google  |title=I-80 Eastbound at Abandoned Weigh Station |url = https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=40.976,+-75.1354&daddr=I-80+and+I-95+teaneck,+nj&geocode=FYA-cQIdWIaF-w%3BFfGTbwId88WW-ykFM6iKN_fCiTF8GZRr5zPfyA&hl=en&mra=ls&sll=40.978732,-75.069923&sspn=0.054042,0.1684&ie=UTF8&t=h&ll=40.904853,-74.602361&spn=0,359.9579&z=15&layer=c&cbll=40.905114,-74.608433&panoid=Vyk7D64Ci18vru0haf_mkg&cbp=12,94.59,,0,5 |work = [[Google Street View]] |publisher = Google |date = September 2008 |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref> After this, the road heads farther north of the railroad tracks and briefly passes through [[Jefferson Township, New Jersey|Jefferson Township]] and [[Rockaway Township, New Jersey|Rockaway Township]] before continuing into [[Wharton, New Jersey|Wharton]]. Here, the freeway has an eastbound exit to CR&nbsp;634 that provides access to [[New Jersey Route 15|Route&nbsp;15]] before it reaches the interchange with Route&nbsp;15 proper that lacks an eastbound exit.<ref name=sld />\n\n[[File:2018-07-31 08 36 48 IMG 9688 will rename and categorize soon.jpg|right|thumb|I-80 westbound past Howard Boulevard interchange in Mount Arlington]]\nThe highway continues back into Rockaway Township as it widens to eight lanes and comes to the CR&nbsp;661 exit near the [[Rockaway Townsquare]] shopping mall. Suburban development near the highway becomes more dense at this point as I-80 briefly passes through a corner of [[Rockaway, New Jersey|Rockaway]] before coming to the interchange with [[County Route 513 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;513]] in Rockaway Township.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The freeway passes over the [[Dover and Rockaway River Railroad]]'s Dover and Rockaway Branch and turns southeast here into [[Denville, New Jersey|Denville]]. In the center of Denville, it has an eastbound exit and westbound entrance serving US&nbsp;46 that also provides access to [[New Jersey Route 53|Route&nbsp;53]]. There is a westbound exit and eastbound entrance serving both US&nbsp;46 and Route&nbsp;53 as the road begins to turn more to the east. I-80 turns south and crosses the Montclair-Boonton Line for a third time before it enters [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]].<ref name=sld /> The highway makes a turn east as it comes into an area of business parks, with the median widening before an interchange serving [[U.S. Route 202 in New Jersey|US&nbsp;202]] and CR&nbsp;654.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The median narrows again before I-80 reaches the [[Interstate 287|I-287]] interchange that also has movements to US&nbsp;46 and Smith Road to and from the east.<ref name=sld />\n\n[[File:I-80 EB approaching US 46 Wayne.jpg|thumb|left|I-80 eastbound approaching the exit for US&nbsp;46 in Wayne]]\nPast I-287, I-80 gains [[local-express lanes]] with a 2-3-3-2 configuration.<ref name=sld /> The road continues past more commercial areas, with the local lanes having an eastbound exit and westbound entrance at CR&nbsp;637.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> After this, there is a large interchange with US&nbsp;46 and the western terminus of [[Interstate 280 (New Jersey)|I-280]], at which point the local-express lanes end.<ref name=sld /> From this point, I-80 continues east through wooded areas as a six-lane freeway, crossing into [[Montville, New Jersey|Montville]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> In Montville, there is a partial interchange providing access to Hook Mountain Road.<ref name=sld /> After a turn to the northeast, the highway comes into [[Fairfield Township, Essex County, New Jersey|Fairfield Township]], [[Essex County, New Jersey|Essex County]], continuing through wooded surroundings as it heads north before turning east. Development near the road increases as it comes to the westbound exit and eastbound entrance with CR 613.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm />\n\n=== Passaic and Bergen counties ===\n[[File:2018-07-21 15 38 55 IMG 8130 will rename and categorize soon.jpg|thumb|right|I-80 eastbound approaching the Route&nbsp;17 interchange in Hackensack]]\nAfter crossing the Passaic River again, I-80 enters [[Wayne, New Jersey|Wayne]] in [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic County]].<ref name=sld /> Here, the road passes under the Montclair-Boonton Line before coming to the Spaghetti Junction with [[New Jersey Route 23|Route&nbsp;23]] and US&nbsp;46 near the [[Willowbrook Mall (Wayne, New Jersey)|Willowbrook Mall]]. At this point, the freeway widens to eight lanes and continues into [[Totowa, New Jersey|Totowa]], passing near more commercial areas as it comes to an interchange with CR&nbsp;642 that has access to and from the west.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> A short distance later, there is a westbound exit and eastbound entrance serving [[New Jersey Route 62|Route&nbsp;62]] and CR&nbsp;646.<ref name=sld /> I-80 crosses the Passaic River a third time and enters [[Woodland Park, New Jersey|Woodland Park]], where it turns to the northeast past suburban neighborhoods and reaches an interchange serving CR&nbsp;636.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> Passing to the north of [[Garret Mountain Reservation]], the freeway enters [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]] and turns east into urban areas as it comes to the interchange at the [[New Jersey Route 19|Route&nbsp;19]] freeway. After Route&nbsp;19, I-80 runs above Paterson on a viaduct, crossing over NJ Transit's [[Main Line (NJ Transit)|Main Line]] before coming to the exit for CR&nbsp;649 (Madison Avenue).  The road returns to ground level near urban neighborhoods as it comes to an eastbound exit and westbound entrance serving Market Street.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> A short distance later, I-80 encounters [[New Jersey Route 20|Route&nbsp;20]] at an interchange.<ref name=sld />\n\n[[File:2014-05-07 16 21 42 View of the eastern end of Interstate 80 from an airplane heading for Newark Airport-cropped.JPG|thumb|left|Eastern terminus of I-80 in Bergen County viewed from an airplane]]\nAfter a fourth crossing of the Passaic River, I-80 comes into [[Elmwood Park, New Jersey|Elmwood Park]] in [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]].  Immediately after the river, the highway reaches the [[County Route 507 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;507]] exit.<ref name=sld /> It continues near suburban neighborhoods, coming to a bridge over [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway]]'s (NYSW) New Jersey Subdivision line, and passes over NJ Transit's [[Bergen County Line]] as it comes to an interchange with the [[Garden State Parkway]] on the border of Elmwood Park and [[Saddle Brook, New Jersey|Saddle Brook]] that also has connections to CR&nbsp;67.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> At the Garden State Parkway, I-80 gains a 2-2 local-express lane configuration eastbound while the westbound direction carries four lanes. The next interchange along the road is with CR&nbsp;79, and is a westbound entrance and an eastbound exit accessible from the local lanes. The freeway passes over the NYSW line again and turns south along the west bank of the [[Saddle River (Passaic River)|Saddle River]], eventually crossing it into [[Lodi, New Jersey|Lodi]].<ref name=sld /> Immediately after, there is a [[diamond interchange]] at Riverview Avenue that provides access to [[New Jersey Route 4|Route&nbsp;4]] and [[New Jersey Route 17|Route&nbsp;17]]. Heading southeast, I-80 passes over NYSW's Lodi Branch line and comes to an interchange at Route&nbsp;17, which provides access to US&nbsp;46 to the south, Route&nbsp;4 to the north, and various local roads. At this point, I-80 runs between the travel lanes of Route&nbsp;17 as it continues into [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]]. Past Route&nbsp;17, I-80 gains a 3-2-2-3 local-express lane configuration and crosses NJ Transit's [[Pascack Valley Line]] before passing through industrial parks and running through a small part of [[South Hackensack, New Jersey|South Hackensack]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> Here, there is an interchange to Green Street before the highway comes into [[Teterboro, New Jersey|Teterboro]]. Turning east, the freeway runs through South Hackensack before entering Hackensack, where an exit provides access to CR&nbsp;124 (Hudson Street).<ref name=sld /> The road passes near neighborhoods before crossing the [[Hackensack River]] into [[Ridgefield Park, New Jersey|Ridgefield Park]], where it passes over NYSW's New Jersey Subdivision line and [[CSX]]'s [[River Subdivision (CSX Transportation)|River Subdivision]] line before there is an exit for 2nd Street.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The freeway passes through a corner of [[Bogota, New Jersey|Bogota]] before it continues into [[Teaneck, New Jersey|Teaneck]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> In Teaneck, I-80 reaches its eastern terminus at the interchange with [[Interstate 95 in New Jersey|I-95]] (the [[New Jersey Turnpike]]). From here, one can head southbound on I-95 and the turnpike towards Newark, or head northbound towards the [[George Washington Bridge]] and [[New York City]].<ref name=gm />\n\n== History ==\nA freeway along the I-80 corridor was first planned in 1936 as a replacement for the cross-state US&nbsp;46, running from the George Washington Bridge west to the Delaware Water Gap and [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |title = Freeways Are Now Urged |newspaper = The New York Times |date = December 13, 1936 |page = 16 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> This proposal was considered again in 1955. Coming off the George Washington Bridge, Route&nbsp;4 and US&nbsp;46 already provided high-speed corridors, but they were overloaded, and so a new corridor in between, the Bergen-Passaic Expressway, was planned to run from the bridge to Paterson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/07/01/305699792.html|title=FREEWAY ROUTE IN JERSEY GIVEN; Fewer Protests Than Were Expected Are Voiced Over Bergen-Passaic Artery FORT LEE ENGLEWOOD LEONIA TEANECK BOGOTA RIDGEFIELD PARK HACKENSACK LODI SADDLE BROOK PATERSON WEST PATERSON TOTOWA AND WAYNE TOWNSHIP|date=July 1, 1956|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=js>{{cite book|title=Joint Study of Arterial Facilities|publisher=[[Port of New York Authority]] and [[Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority]] |year=1955}}</ref> The planned route west to the Delaware Water Gap was designated in 1956 as Federal Aid Interstate Route&nbsp;101 by the [[New Jersey State Highway Department]].<ref name=nyt2>{{cite news |last = Wright |first = George Cable |title = Jersey Acts to Speed U.S. Aid for Its $388.5 Million Freeway |newspaper = The New York Times |date = March 5, 1958 |page = |issn = 0362-4331 }}{{page needed|date=July 2019}}</ref> It first received the I-82 designation before finally becoming a part of I-80 in 1958.<ref name=\"1957 map\">{{cite map |author = [[Public Roads Administration]] |author2 = [[American Association of State Highway Officials]] |year = 1957 |title = Official Numbering for the National System of Interstate and Defense Highways, as Adopted by the American Association of State Highway Officials, August 14, 1957 |url = https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Interstate_Highway_plan_August_14,_1957.jpg |scale = Scale not given |location = Washington, DC |publisher = [[Federal Works Agency]] |accessdate =January 13, 2010 |via = [[Wikimedia Commons]] }}</ref><ref name=nyt3>{{cite news |last = Wright |first = George Cable |title = New Roads with New Numbers Will Parallel Old U.S. Routes |newspaper = The New York Times |date = September 19, 1958 |page = 29|issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> The easternmost section of the route, leading to the bridge, had become part of I-95.<ref name=nyt3 />\n\nThe section of I-80 through the Delaware Water Gap had already opened on December 16, 1953, running from the Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge to Route&nbsp;94 at Columbia.<ref name=nyt4>{{cite news |title = New Span Crosses Delaware River; Fine, Driscoll at Ceremonies for Water Gap Bridge\u2014Road to Link Poconos and New York |newspaper = The New York Times |date = December 17, 1953 |page = 51 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> This road was signed as a realignment of [[U.S. Route 611|US&nbsp;611]] from Pennsylvania, later receiving the I-80 designation. The old alignment of US&nbsp;611 in Pennsylvania had become US&nbsp;611 Alternate.<ref name=\"PennDOT 1950 back\">{{cite map|publisher=Pennsylvania Department of Highways|title=Official Road Map of Pennsylvania (back)| url=http://www.dot7.state.pa.us/BPR_PDF_FILES/MAPS/Statewide/Historic_OTMs/1950bk.pdf|year=1950|accessdate=January 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"esso\" /> By 1966, I-80 had been completed from Netcong to Denville and from Paterson to I-95.<ref name=\"esso\">{{cite map |author1 = [[Esso]] |title = United States featuring the Interstate Highway System |year = 1966 |author2 = [[General Drafting]] |scale = |location = |publisher = }}{{full|date= July 2019}}</ref> By 1969, the section between I-280 in Parsippany and Route&nbsp;23 in Wayne was finished. Also around this time, US&nbsp;611 was moved off of I-80 and back into Pennsylvania, replacing US&nbsp;611 Alternate.<ref name=\"chevron\">{{cite map |author1 = [[Chevron Oil Company]] |title = Map of New Jersey |year = 1969 |author2=[[H.M. Gousha]] |scale = |location = |publisher = }}{{full|date= July 2019}}</ref> By 1971, the section between Wayne and [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]] was completed along with the part between US&nbsp;202 and I-280.<ref name=nyt5>{{cite news |last = Shipler |first = David K. |title = New Highways Shaping Future of City's Suburbs; New Superhighways Shaping Future of City's Suburbs |newspaper = The New York Times |date = August 19, 1971 |page = 1 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> A {{convert|3.5|mi|km|adj=on}} section between US&nbsp;46 in [[Denville, New Jersey|Denville]] and US&nbsp;202 [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]], was opened in September 1973.<ref name=nyt6>{{cite news |last = Burks |first = Edward C. |title = Vital Stretch of Route 80 Opens in Jersey, Ending Big Bottleneck; Stretch of Route 80 Opens and Eliminates Bottleneck |newspaper = The New York Times |date = September 15, 1973 |page = 65 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> Also in 1973, the section between US&nbsp;206 in Netcong and US&nbsp;46 and Route&nbsp;94 in Columbia was completed, and the interchange in Columbia was realigned into a complex array of ramps.<ref name=nyt7>{{cite news |title = Missing Link of I-80 Opened in Ceremony Near Columbia |newspaper = [[The New York Times]] |date = November 9, 1973 |page = 86 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, two rest areas along I-80 were shut down due to chronic use for homosexual activities. The rest area in [[Lodi, New Jersey|Lodi]], next to westbound exit&nbsp;63, shut down on June 30, 1982 on request of the [[New Jersey State Police]]. Local lawyers noted that an uptick of summons were given at the rest area, including one motorist cited for not using parking lights. The State Police decided that it was not worth patrolling as it was an unattended rest area.<ref>{{cite news |title = Controversial Rest Site on Interstate is Closed |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14384914/i80_lodi_rest_area_july_8_1982/ |access-date= October 13, 2017 |work = [[The Asbury Park Press]] |date = July 8, 1982 |page = 48 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] }} {{open access}}</ref> The rest area at [[Roxbury, New Jersey|Roxbury]] in [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris County]] shut down in October 1982.<ref name=\"roxburycloses\">{{cite news |last1 = Mitkwoski |first1 = Michelle |title = Route 80 'Gay' Spots Shut for Time Being |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14385547/80_roxbury_closed_october_30_1982/ |access-date = October 13, 2017 |work = The Daily Record |location = |date = October 30, 1982 |page = 22 |via = Newspapers.com }} {{open access}}</ref> Opened in the 1970s, the borough noted that it was impossible to control the activity going on at the location, including homosexual activities, alcohol and drug parties, theft and lewd acts.<ref name=\"roxburyproposals\">{{cite news |last1 = McKeel |first1 = Stuart |title = Roxbury Twp. Fights Proposal for Rest Areas |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14385260/roxbury_stop_june_10_1990/ |access-date = October 13, 2017 |work = The Daily Record |date = June 10, 1990 |page = 3 |via = Newspapers.com }} {{open access}}</ref> However, citing numerous accidents and needing a place for trucks to be able to rest,<ref name=\"roxburyproposals\" /> the stop re-opened on August 14, 1991 for truckers only.<ref name=\"roxburyreopens\">{{cite news |last1 = McKeel |first1 = Stuart |title = Rt. 80 Rest Area Reopens\u2014for Trucks |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14384940/roxbury_reopens_august_14_1991/ |access-date = October 13, 2017 |work = The Daily Record |date = August 14, 1991 |via = Newspapers.com }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, [[high-occupancy vehicle lane]]s were built along I-80 between Rockaway and Parsippany. These HOV lanes, along with the ones that had been built on I-287, were opened to regular traffic in 1998 due to lack of usage, and the state did not have to repay the federal government the $240&nbsp;million to build the lanes.<ref name=nyt8>{{cite news |last = Berger |first = Joseph |title = Our Towns; H.O.V. Lanes: A 30-Mile Test That Failed |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/01/nyregion/our-towns-hov-lanes-a-30-mile-test-that-failed.html |newspaper = The New York Times |date = December 1, 1998 |access-date = December 22, 2009 }}</ref> On June 22, 2001, a tanker crashed on a westbound bridge on I-80 in Denville, causing a fiery explosion that damaged the bridge and forced its demolition.<ref name=nyt9>{{cite news |last = Murphy |first = Dean E. |title = Drivers May Face Months of Delays After Fiery Crash Forces Demolition of I-80 Span |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/24/nyregion/drivers-may-face-months-delays-after-fiery-crash-forces-demolition-80-span.html |newspaper = The New York Times |date = June 24, 2001 |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref> A temporary bridge had to be built and traffic on this part of I-80 as well as adjacent roads was snarled; in addition, a state of emergency had been declared for Morris County.<ref name=nyt10>{{cite news |department = Metro Briefing |title = New Jersey: Trenton: Route 80 Emergency Declared |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/04/nyregion/metro-briefing-new-jersey-trenton-route-80-emergency-declared.html |newspaper = The New York Times |date = July 4, 2001 |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref> The new I-80 bridge opened in September 2001.<ref name=njdot>{{cite press release |author = New Jersey Department of Transportation |url = http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/about/press/2001/090501c.shtm |title = NJDOT Will Begin Work to Re-Open I-80 in Morris County |date = September 5, 2001 |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nI-80, like many other highways in New Jersey, once had solar powered emergency [[call box]]es every {{convert|1|mi|km}}, however with the advent of cell phones the usage of these call boxes became extremely limited. To save on maintenance costs, the NJDOT removed these call boxes in 2005.<ref name=pressac>{{cite news |last = Barlas |first = Thomas |title = Last Call for N.J.'s Roadside Call Boxes |work = [[The Press of Atlantic City]] |date = February 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, NJDOT held a public meeting regarding a proposed rock wall along I-80 in the Delaware Water Gap National Recreation Area. The $60 million project, dubbed the \"Jurassic Park fence\", would involve construction of a {{convert|60|ft|m|adj=on}} metal fence between mile marker 1.04 and 1.05 to prevent rocks from falling onto the highway. According to NJDOT, the area has the highest rockfall hazard in the state. Nine rockfall incidents and one fatality have been reported between 2001 and 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cassi |first1=Sarah |title=Controversial I-80 project in Delaware Water Gap, dubbed the 'Jurassic Park fence,\u2019 goes before the public |url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/warren-county/2019/06/controversial-i-80-project-in-delaware-water-gap-dubbed-the-jurassic-park-fence-goes-before-the-public.html |accessdate=August 22, 2019 |agency=lehighvalleylive.com |date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Exit list ==\n{{jcttop|exit|state=NJ|length_ref=<ref name=sld />}}\n{{jctint|exit\n|river=[[Delaware River]]\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.00\n|mspan=2\n|exit=\u2013\n|road={{jct|state=PA|I|80|dir1=west|PA|611|to2=yes|city1=Stroudsburg|city2=Delaware Water Gap}}\n|notes=Continuation into [[Pennsylvania]]; toll booths across state line\n}}\n{{jctbridge|exit\n|mile=none\n|line=yes\n|type=toll\n|bridge=[[Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge]] (Westbound toll, cash or [[E-ZPass]])}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|county=Warren\n|cspan=9\n|location=Hardwick Township\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.10\n|exit=1\n|road=[[Millbrook, New Jersey|Millbrook]], [[Flatbrookville, New Jersey|Flatbrookville]]\n|notes=Via [[Old Mine Road]]; last westbound exit before toll}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=0.87\n|exit=\u2013\n|road=[[Delaware Water Gap National Recreation Area]]\n|notes=Access to [[u-turn]] and [[Appalachian Trail]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Knowlton Township\n|lspan=5\n|mile=2.05\n|place=[[Weigh station]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=3.39\n|exit=\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Hainesburg Road\n|notes=Westbound exit and entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=4.20\n|exit=4A\n|road=[[Columbia, New Jersey|Columbia]]\n|notes=Westbound exit is via exit 4B; via Decatur Street}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=4.58\n|mspan=2\n|exit=4B\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=east|to2=to|PA|611|location1=[[Portland, Pennsylvania|Portland, PA]]|city2=Buttzville}}\n|notes=Western terminus of US&nbsp;46}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=none\n|exit=4C\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|NJ|94|dir1=north|city1=Blairstown}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Hope Township\n|mile=12.03\n|exit=12\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|CR|521|to2=to|CR|519|city1=Blairstown|city2=Hope}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Allamuchy Township\n|mile=19.88\n|exit=19\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|CR|517|city1=Hackettstown|city2=Allamuchy|city3=Andover}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|county=Morris\n|cspan=24\n|location=Mount Olive Township\n|mile=25.25\n|exit=25\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|206|dir1=north|city1=Stanhope|city2=Newton}}\n|notes=West end of [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with US&nbsp;206}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Netcong\n|mile=26.25\n|exit=26\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=west|city1=Budd Lake|city2=Hackettstown}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Roxbury\n|lspan=3\n|mile=27.19\n|mspan=2\n|exit=27A\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|206|dir1=south|city1=Somerville}}\n|notes=East end of concurrency with US&nbsp;206}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=none\n|exit=27B\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|NJ|183|dir1=north|city1=Netcong}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=28.91\n|exit=28\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=east|to2=to|NJ|10|city1=Ledgewood|city2=Lake Hopatcong}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Mount Arlington\n|mile=30.61\n|exit=30\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|CR|615|county1=Morris|noshield1=yes|name1=Howard Boulevard|city1=Mount Arlington}}\n|notes=Access to [[Mount Arlington station]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Wharton\n|lspan=2\n|mile=33.58\n|exit=34\n|espan=2\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|to1=to|NJ|15|name1=[[County Route 634 (Morris County, New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;634]]|city1=Wharton|city2=Dover|city3=Sparta}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit only; formerly exit&nbsp;33}}\n{{NJint\n|mile=34.02\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|to1=to|NJ|15|city1=Wharton|city2=Jefferson|city3=Sparta}}\n|notes=No eastbound exit; signed as exits 34A (south) and 34B (north)}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Rockaway Township\n|lspan=2\n|mile=35.33\n|exit=35\n|road=[[Mount Hope, New Jersey|Mount Hope]], [[Dover, New Jersey|Dover]]\n|notes=Signed as exits 35A (south) and 35B (north) westbound;<br />access via [[County Route 661 (Morris County, New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;661]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=37.63\n|exit=37\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|CR|513|city1=Hibernia|city2=Rockaway}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Denville\n|lspan=2\n|mile=38.81\n|exit=38\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=east|to2=to|NJ|53|city1=Denville|extra=rail}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance; to [[Denville (NJT station)|Denville station]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=39.57\n|exit=39\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=east|to2=to|NJ|53|city1=Denville|extra=rail}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance; to [[Denville (NJT station)|Denville station]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Parsippany-Troy Hills\n|lspan=11\n|mile=42.46\n|mspan=3\n|exit=42A\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|202|dir1=south|city1=Morris Plains}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=none\n|exit=42B\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|to1=to|US|46|city1=Parsippany}}\n|notes=No eastbound exit}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=none\n|exit=42C\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|202|dir1=north|city1=Parsippany}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=43.62\n|exit=43\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|I|287|city1=Boonton|city2=Morristown|city3=Mahwah}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 43A (south) and 43B (north) westbound; exit 41 on I-287}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=\n|place=Western terminus of [[local-express lanes]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=\n|exit=\u2013\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|to1=to|US|46|road=Smith Road}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance via exit 43B}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=45.34\n|exit=45\n|type=incomplete\n|road=[[Lake Hiawatha, New Jersey|Lake Hiawatha]], [[Whippany, New Jersey|Whippany]]\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance via [[County Route 637 (Morris County, New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;637]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=46.36\n|exit=47A\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|I|280|dir1=east|location1=[[The Oranges]]|city2=Newark}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=\n|place=Eastern terminus of local-express lanes}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=46.50\n|mspan=2\n|exit=47B\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=east|location1=[[The Caldwells]]|city2=Montclair}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=none\n|exit=47\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=west|city1=Parsippany}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Montville\n|mile=47.83\n|exit=48\n|type=incomplete\n|road=[[Montville, New Jersey|Montville]], [[Pine Brook, Morris County, New Jersey|Pine Brook]]\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance; <br />access via Hook Mountain Road}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|county=Essex\n|location=Fairfield Township\n|ctdab=Essex\n|mile=52.48\n|exit=52\n|type=incomplete\n|road=[[Lincoln Park, New Jersey|Lincoln Park]], [[Fairfield Township, Essex County, New Jersey|Fairfield]], [[The Caldwells]]\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance via [[County Route 613 (Essex County, New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;613]]}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|county=Passaic\n|cspan=11\n|location=Wayne\n|lspan=2\n|mile=53.62\n|mspan=2\n|exit=53\n|espan=2\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|dir1=east|to2=to|NJ|3|city1=Wayne|city2=Clifton|location3=[[Lincoln Tunnel]]}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance;<br />access to [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]]|}}\n{{NJint\n|mile=none\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|US|46|NJ|23|city1=Wayne|city2=Butler|city3=Verona}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Totowa\n|lspan=2\n|mile=54.73\n|exit=54\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|CR|642|county1=Passaic|noshield1=yes|name1=Minnisink Road|city1=Little Falls|city2=Totowa}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=55.21\n|exit=55\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|NJ|62|noshield1=yes|dir1=south|CR|646|county2=Passaic|noshield2=yes|name2=Union Boulevard|city1=Little Falls|city2=Totowa}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance;<br />signed as exits 55A (south) and 55B (north)}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Woodland Park\n|mile=57.07\n|exit=56\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|CR|636|county1=Passaic|noshield1=yes|name1=Squirrelwood Road|city1=Woodland Park|city2=Paterson}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 56A (south) and 56B (north) eastbound}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Paterson\n|lspan=6\n|mile=58.22\n|mspan=2\n|exit=57A\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|NJ|19|dir1=south|city1=Clifton}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=none\n|exit=57B\n|road=[[Paterson, New Jersey|Downtown Paterson]]\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=58.37\n|exit=57C\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|CR|509|noshield1=yes|name1=Main Street|city1=Paterson}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=59.06\n|exit=58\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|CR|649|county1=Passaic|noshield1=yes|name1=Madison Avenue|city1=Paterson|city2=Clifton}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 58A (south) and 58B (north)}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=60.04\n|exit=59\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Market Street \u2013 [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]]\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=60.41\n|exit=60\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|NJ|20|city1=Hawthorne|city2=Passaic}}\n|notes=Westbound exit to Route 20 south is via exit 59}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|county=Bergen\n|cspan=14\n|location=Elmwood Park\n|mile=60.81\n|exit=61\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|CR|507|city1=Garfield|city2=Elmwood Park}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Saddle Brook\n|lspan=3\n|mile=62.34\n|exit=62A\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|GSP||city1=Saddle Brook|road=Midland Avenue}}\n|type=toll\n|notes=Signed as exit 62 westbound; commercial vehicles prohibited on the parkway}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=\n|place=Western terminus of local-express lanes}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=\n|exit=62B\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|CR|79|county1=Bergen|noshield1=yes|name1=Saddle River Road|city1=Fair Lawn|city2=Lodi}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Lodi\n|lspan=2\n|mile=63.82\n|exit=63\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|to1=to|NJ|4|NJ|17|city1=Rochelle Park|city2=Paramus|city3=Lodi|city4=Fair Lawn}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=\n|place=Eastern terminus of local-express lanes}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Hackensack\n|lspan=3\n|mile=65.19\n|exit=64A\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|NJ|17|dir1=north|to2=to|NJ|4|city1=Rochelle Park|city2=Paramus}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=65.05\n|mile2=65.19\n|exit=64\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|NJ|17|dir1=south|to2=to|US|46|dir2=east|city1=Hasbrouck Heights|city2=Newark}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=65.40\n|exit=64B\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|to1=to|NJ|17|dir1=south|city1=Hasbrouck Heights|city2=Newark}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location1=Teterboro\n|location2=South Hackensack\n|mile=65.67\n|exit=65\n|road=Green Street&nbsp;\u2013 [[Teterboro, New Jersey|Teterboro]], [[South Hackensack, New Jersey|South Hackensack]]\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Hackensack\n|mile=66.55\n|exit=66\n|road={{jctname|state=NJ|CR|124|county1=Bergen|noshield1=yes|name1=Hudson Street|city1=Hackensack|city2=Little Ferry}}\n|notes=}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Ridgefield Park\n|mile=67.22\n|exit=67\n|type=incomplete\n|road=[[Bogota, New Jersey|Bogota]], [[Ridgefield Park, New Jersey|Ridgefield Park]]\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance via 2nd Street}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|location=Teaneck\n|lspan=2\n|mile=68.17\n|exit=68A\n|type=incomplete\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|I|95|dir1=south|NJTP||dir2=south|US|46|location1=[[Meadowlands Sports Complex]]}}\n|notes=I-95 exit 69; eastbound exit and westbound entrance}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|mile=68.54\n|exit=\u2013\n|road={{jct|state=NJ|I|95|dir1=north|location1=[[George Washington Bridge]]|location2=[[New York City]]}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus}}\n{{jctbtm|col=7|keys=concur,incomplete,toll}}\n\n== Auxiliary routes ==\n* {{jct|state=NJ|I|280}}, known locally as the Essex Freeway\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n* {{Portal-inline|New Jersey}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n* [http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/refdata/traffic_orders/speed/rt80.shtm Speed Limits for New Jersey State Roads: Interstate 80]\n\n{{compact state detail browse|type=I|route=80|state=New Jersey|statebefore=Pennsylvania}}\n{{3di|80}}\n\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in New Jersey|80]]\n[[Category:Interstate 80|New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Bergen County, New Jersey|80]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Passaic County, New Jersey|80]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Essex County, New Jersey|80]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Morris County, New Jersey|80]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Sussex County, New Jersey|80]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Warren County, New Jersey|80]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Highway detail hatnote|Interstate 80}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state = NJ\n|type = I\n|route = 80\n|alternate_name = Christopher Columbus Highway\n|map = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=line|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|stroke-width=3}}\n|map_custom = yes\n|map_notes = I-80 highlighted in red\n|map_alt = A map of New Jersey showing major roads. I-80 runs east-west across the northern part of the state.\n|maint=[[New Jersey Department of Transportation|NJDOT]] and [[Delaware River Joint Toll Bridge Commission|DRJTBC]]\n|length_mi = 68.54\n|length_ref =<ref name=sld>{{cite web |author = [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]] |date = April 2014 |url = http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/refdata/sldiag/pdf/00000080__-.pdf |title = I-80 Straight Line Diagram |department = Roadway Information and Traffic Monitoring System Program |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation |access-date = March 17, 2020 }}</ref>\n|history = Established 1958<ref name=\"1957 map\" /><br />Completed in 1973<ref name=nyt7 />\n|direction_a = West\n|terminus_a = {{Jct|state=PA|I|80}} at [[Pennsylvania]] border in [[Hardwick Township, New Jersey|Hardwick Township]]\n|junction = {{plainlist|\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|US|46|NJ|94}} in [[Knowlton Township, New Jersey|Knowlton Township]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|US|206|NJ|183}} in [[Roxbury, New Jersey|Roxbury]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|15}} in [[Wharton, New Jersey|Wharton]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|I|287}} in [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|I|280|US|46}} in Parsippany-Troy Hills\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|US|46|NJ|23}} in [[Wayne, New Jersey|Wayne]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|19}} in [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|20}} in Paterson\n* {{jct|state=NJ|GSP}} in [[Saddle Brook, New Jersey|Saddle Brook]]\n* {{Jct|state=NJ|NJ|17}} in [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]]\n}}\n|direction_b = East\n|terminus_b = {{Jct|state=NJ|I|95|NJTP|}} in [[Teaneck, New Jersey|Teaneck]]\n|counties = [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren]], [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]], [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris]], [[Essex County, New Jersey|Essex]], [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen]]\n|previous_type = NJ\n|previous_route = 79\n|next_type = NJ\n|next_route = 81\n}}\n\n'''Interstate 80''' ('''I-80''') is a major [[Interstate Highway]] in the [[United States]], running from [[San Francisco]], California eastward to the [[New York City Metropolitan Area]]. In [[New Jersey]], I-80 runs for {{convert|68.54|mi|km}} from the [[Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge]] at the [[Pennsylvania]] state line to its eastern terminus at [[Interstate 95 in New Jersey|I-95]] in [[Teaneck, New Jersey|Teaneck]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]]. I-95 continues from the end of I-80 to the [[George Washington Bridge]] for access to [[New York City]]. The highway runs parallel to [[U.S. Route&nbsp;46]] (US&nbsp;46) through rural areas of [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren]] and [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]] counties before heading into more suburban surroundings in [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris County]]. As the road continues into [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic]] and Bergen counties, it heads into more urban areas. The [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]] (NJDOT) identifies I-80 within the state as the '''Christopher Columbus Highway'''.<ref name=sld />\n\nA freeway along the I-80 corridor had been planned in 1936 and again in 1955 to provide relief along US&nbsp;46 between the George Washington Bridge and the [[Delaware Water Gap]]. With the establishment of the Interstate Highway System, this planned freeway, which had been identified in some planning documents as the '''Bergen-Passaic Expressway''', would be incorporated into I-80. The freeway was built across New Jersey in various stages from the 1960s to 1973. The westernmost four miles in New Jersey was originally a rerouting of [[U.S. Route 611|US&nbsp;611]] when built; that route was later realigned back into Pennsylvania. In the 1990s, [[high-occupancy vehicle lane]]s had existed on a part of I-80 in Morris County but were opened to regular traffic due to under-use.\n\n== Route description ==\n=== Warren and Sussex counties ===\n[[File:2018-06-28 09 19 00 View east along Interstate 80 just west of Exit 1 within the Delaware Water Gap in Hardwick Township, Warren County, New Jersey.jpg|thumb|left|View east along I-80 just after entering New Jersey within the Delaware Water Gap National Recreation Area]]\nI-80 enters [[Hardwick Township, New Jersey|Hardwick Township]], [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren County]] from Pennsylvania on the [[Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge]] over the [[Delaware River]], maintained by the [[Delaware River Joint Toll Bridge Commission]] (DRJTBC).<ref name=sld /> In addition to carrying I-80, this bridge also carries the [[Appalachian Trail]] over the Delaware River.  From this point, the four-lane freeway heads south along the east bank of the river through the [[Delaware Water Gap]], immediately reaching a westbound exit and eastbound entrance for [[Old Mine Road]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm>{{google maps |url = https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=40.976,+-75.1354&daddr=I-80+and+I-95+teaneck,+nj&geocode=%3BFfGTbwId88WW-ykFM6iKN_fCiTF8GZRr5zPfyA&hl=en&mra=ls&sll=40.978732,-75.069923&sspn=0.054042,0.1684&ie=UTF8&t=h&z=10 |title = Overview of Interstate 80 in New Jersey |access-date = January 14, 2010 }}</ref> Now maintained by [[New Jersey Department of Transportation|NJDOT]], the road makes a sharp turn to the east and comes to a [[U-turn]] ramp in both directions that also has access to the Appalachian Trail.<ref name=sld /> NJDOT has proposed a controversial rock wall along the stretch to handle rock slides.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.njherald.com/20180219/a-rock-fence-or-a-stone-wall|title=In Water Gap, a rock fence or a stone wall?|last=Scruton|first=Bruce A.|date=February 19, 2018|website=New Jersey Herald|language=en|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref> The highway heads south again and enters [[Knowlton Township, New Jersey|Knowlton Township]], where it comes to another set of U-turn ramps that also includes a [[weigh station]] in the eastbound direction. After turning southeast and leaving the Delaware Water Gap, the road has a westbound [[right-in/right-out]] for Hainesburg Road before crossing under the abandoned [[Lackawanna Cutoff]]. I-80 widens to six lanes and reaches a complex interchange with the western terminus of [[U.S. Route 46|US&nbsp;46]], [[New Jersey Route 94|Route&nbsp;94]], and Decatur Street in [[Columbia, New Jersey|Columbia]], where development near the route increases. After this interchange, the freeway turns east away from the Delaware River and crosses over [[Paulins Kill]] before it continues through wooded and hilly areas containing some farms, with the eastbound direction widening from three to four lanes and the highway median also widens. A [[scenic overlook]] of the Delaware Water Gap is located in the westbound direction while a [[rest area]] is located in the eastbound direction.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm />\n\n[[File:80Expy Knowlton.JPG|right|thumb|I-80 westbound in [[Knowlton Township, New Jersey|Knowlton Township]]|alt=One direction of a freeway running through woodland]]\n\nUpon crossing into [[Blairstown Township, New Jersey|Blairstown Township]], the eastbound direction narrows down to three lanes.<ref name=sld /> In [[Hope Township, New Jersey|Hope Township]], I-80 reaches an interchange with [[County Route 521 (New Jersey)|County Route&nbsp;521]] (CR&nbsp;521) that also provides access to [[County Route 519 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;519]] and the [[Land of Make Believe (amusement park)|Land of Make Believe]] amusement park.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The highway widens to eight lanes briefly after this interchange before narrowing to six lanes. In [[Frelinghuysen Township, New Jersey|Frelinghuysen Township]], the freeway carries four lanes eastbound and three lanes westbound. Upon coming into [[Allamuchy Township, New Jersey|Allamuchy Township]], I-80 has six lanes before gaining a fourth eastbound lane as it comes to the [[County Route 517 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;517]] exit.<ref name=sld /> This exit gives the highway access to [[Allamuchy Mountain State Park]].<ref name=gm /> Following this, the road runs through densely forested areas of Allamuchy Mountain State Park, coming to two pairs of rest areas with no facilities in both directions. The eastbound direction becomes three lanes again before the road passes through [[Byram Township, New Jersey|Byram Township]] in [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex County]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm />\n\n=== Morris and Essex counties ===\n[[File:I80easthopetownshipyuvrajr.JPG|left|thumb|I-80 eastbound in Hope Township]]\nUpon crossing the [[Musconetcong River]], I-80 enters [[Mount Olive Township, New Jersey|Mount Olive Township]] in [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris County]] and passes through more woodland with a narrower median. The road comes to a [[trumpet interchange]] with [[U.S. Route 206|US&nbsp;206]] and forms a [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with that route as it bypasses [[Netcong, New Jersey|Netcong]] to the south.  After turning southeast and passing near suburban business parks, the highway crosses over [[NJ Transit]]\u2019s [[Morristown Line]]/[[Montclair-Boonton Line]] and reaches a partial interchange with US&nbsp;46.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> This interchange has only a westbound exit and eastbound entrance. The freeway crosses a small corner of Netcong and Mount Olive Township again before continuing into [[Roxbury Township, New Jersey|Roxbury Township]], where it comes to a modified [[cloverleaf interchange]].<ref name=sld /> At this interchange, [[New Jersey Route 183|Route&nbsp;183]] heads north into Netcong and US&nbsp;206 splits from I-80 by heading south. The road continues through wooded areas containing some suburban development as it comes to the CR&nbsp;631 interchange, which also provides access to eastbound US&nbsp;46.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The road crosses the NJ Transit line again and parallels it a short distance to the north as it comes into [[Mount Arlington, New Jersey|Mount Arlington]] and reaches the Howard Boulevard exit, serving [[Mount Arlington station]].<ref name=sld /> I-80 continues back into Roxbury Township and comes to a westbound truck rest area with the eastbound one being abandoned.<ref name=sld /><ref name=njdot2>{{cite web |url = http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/refdata/traffic_orders/rest_stops/rt80.shtm |department= NJDOT Traffic Regulations |title = Traffic and Parking in Rest Areas: Interstate 80 |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=gsv>{{cite web |author = Google  |title=I-80 Eastbound at Abandoned Weigh Station |url = https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=40.976,+-75.1354&daddr=I-80+and+I-95+teaneck,+nj&geocode=FYA-cQIdWIaF-w%3BFfGTbwId88WW-ykFM6iKN_fCiTF8GZRr5zPfyA&hl=en&mra=ls&sll=40.978732,-75.069923&sspn=0.054042,0.1684&ie=UTF8&t=h&ll=40.904853,-74.602361&spn=0,359.9579&z=15&layer=c&cbll=40.905114,-74.608433&panoid=Vyk7D64Ci18vru0haf_mkg&cbp=12,94.59,,0,5 |work = [[Google Street View]] |publisher = Google |date = September 2008 |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref> After this, the road heads farther north of the railroad tracks and briefly passes through [[Jefferson Township, New Jersey|Jefferson Township]] and [[Rockaway Township, New Jersey|Rockaway Township]] before continuing into [[Wharton, New Jersey|Wharton]]. Here, the freeway has an eastbound exit to CR&nbsp;634 that provides access to [[New Jersey Route 15|Route&nbsp;15]] before it reaches the interchange with Route&nbsp;15 proper that lacks an eastbound exit.<ref name=sld />\n\n[[File:2018-07-31 08 36 48 IMG 9688 will rename and categorize soon.jpg|right|thumb|I-80 westbound past Howard Boulevard interchange in Mount Arlington]]\nThe highway continues back into Rockaway Township as it widens to eight lanes and comes to the CR&nbsp;661 exit near the [[Rockaway Townsquare]] shopping mall. Suburban development near the highway becomes more dense at this point as I-80 briefly passes through a corner of [[Rockaway, New Jersey|Rockaway]] before coming to the interchange with [[County Route 513 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;513]] in Rockaway Township.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The freeway passes over the [[Dover and Rockaway River Railroad]]'s Dover and Rockaway Branch and turns southeast here into [[Denville, New Jersey|Denville]]. In the center of Denville, it has an eastbound exit and westbound entrance serving US&nbsp;46 that also provides access to [[New Jersey Route 53|Route&nbsp;53]]. There is a westbound exit and eastbound entrance serving both US&nbsp;46 and Route&nbsp;53 as the road begins to turn more to the east. I-80 turns south and crosses the Montclair-Boonton Line for a third time before it enters [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]].<ref name=sld /> The highway makes a turn east as it comes into an area of business parks, with the median widening before an interchange serving [[U.S. Route 202 in New Jersey|US&nbsp;202]] and CR&nbsp;654.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The median narrows again before I-80 reaches the [[Interstate 287|I-287]] interchange that also has movements to US&nbsp;46 and Smith Road to and from the east.<ref name=sld />\n\n[[File:I-80 EB approaching US 46 Wayne.jpg|thumb|left|I-80 eastbound approaching the exit for US&nbsp;46 in Wayne]]\nPast I-287, I-80 gains [[local-express lanes]] with a 2-3-3-2 configuration.<ref name=sld /> The road continues past more commercial areas, with the local lanes having an eastbound exit and westbound entrance at CR&nbsp;637.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> After this, there is a large interchange with US&nbsp;46 and the western terminus of [[Interstate 280 (New Jersey)|I-280]], at which point the local-express lanes end.<ref name=sld /> From this point, I-80 continues east through wooded areas as a six-lane freeway, crossing into [[Montville, New Jersey|Montville]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> In Montville, there is a partial interchange providing access to Hook Mountain Road.<ref name=sld /> After a turn to the northeast, the highway comes into [[Fairfield Township, Essex County, New Jersey|Fairfield Township]], [[Essex County, New Jersey|Essex County]], continuing through wooded surroundings as it heads north before turning east. Development near the road increases as it comes to the westbound exit and eastbound entrance with CR 613.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm />\n\n=== Passaic and Bergen counties ===\n[[File:2018-07-21 15 38 55 IMG 8130 will rename and categorize soon.jpg|thumb|right|I-80 eastbound approaching the Route&nbsp;17 interchange in Hackensack]]\nAfter crossing the Passaic River again, I-80 enters [[Wayne, New Jersey|Wayne]] in [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic County]].<ref name=sld /> Here, the road passes under the Montclair-Boonton Line before coming to the Spaghetti Junction with [[New Jersey Route 23|Route&nbsp;23]] and US&nbsp;46 near the [[Willowbrook Mall (Wayne, New Jersey)|Willowbrook Mall]]. At this point, the freeway widens to eight lanes and continues into [[Totowa, New Jersey|Totowa]], passing near more commercial areas as it comes to an interchange with CR&nbsp;642 that has access to and from the west.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> A short distance later, there is a westbound exit and eastbound entrance serving [[New Jersey Route 62|Route&nbsp;62]] and CR&nbsp;646.<ref name=sld /> I-80 crosses the Passaic River a third time and enters [[Woodland Park, New Jersey|Woodland Park]], where it turns to the northeast past suburban neighborhoods and reaches an interchange serving CR&nbsp;636.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> Passing to the north of [[Garret Mountain Reservation]], the freeway enters [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]] and turns east into urban areas as it comes to the interchange at the [[New Jersey Route 19|Route&nbsp;19]] freeway. After Route&nbsp;19, I-80 runs above Paterson on a viaduct, crossing over NJ Transit's [[Main Line (NJ Transit)|Main Line]] before coming to the exit for CR&nbsp;649 (Madison Avenue).  The road returns to ground level near urban neighborhoods as it comes to an eastbound exit and westbound entrance serving Market Street.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> A short distance later, I-80 encounters [[New Jersey Route 20|Route&nbsp;20]] at an interchange.<ref name=sld />\n\n[[File:2014-05-07 16 21 42 View of the eastern end of Interstate 80 from an airplane heading for Newark Airport-cropped.JPG|thumb|left|Eastern terminus of I-80 in Bergen County viewed from an airplane]]\nAfter a fourth crossing of the Passaic River, I-80 comes into [[Elmwood Park, New Jersey|Elmwood Park]] in [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]].  Immediately after the river, the highway reaches the [[County Route 507 (New Jersey)|CR&nbsp;507]] exit.<ref name=sld /> It continues near suburban neighborhoods, coming to a bridge over [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway]]'s (NYSW) New Jersey Subdivision line, and passes over NJ Transit's [[Bergen County Line]] as it comes to an interchange with the [[Garden State Parkway]] on the border of Elmwood Park and [[Saddle Brook, New Jersey|Saddle Brook]] that also has connections to CR&nbsp;67.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> At the Garden State Parkway, I-80 gains a 2-2 local-express lane configuration eastbound while the westbound direction carries four lanes. The next interchange along the road is with CR&nbsp;79, and is a westbound entrance and an eastbound exit accessible from the local lanes. The freeway passes over the NYSW line again and turns south along the west bank of the [[Saddle River (Passaic River)|Saddle River]], eventually crossing it into [[Lodi, New Jersey|Lodi]].<ref name=sld /> Immediately after, there is a [[diamond interchange]] at Riverview Avenue that provides access to [[New Jersey Route 4|Route&nbsp;4]] and [[New Jersey Route 17|Route&nbsp;17]]. Heading southeast, I-80 passes over NYSW's Lodi Branch line and comes to an interchange at Route&nbsp;17, which provides access to US&nbsp;46 to the south, Route&nbsp;4 to the north, and various local roads. At this point, I-80 runs between the travel lanes of Route&nbsp;17 as it continues into [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]]. Past Route&nbsp;17, I-80 gains a 3-2-2-3 local-express lane configuration and crosses NJ Transit's [[Pascack Valley Line]] before passing through industrial parks and running through a small part of [[South Hackensack, New Jersey|South Hackensack]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> Here, there is an interchange to Green Street before the highway comes into [[Teterboro, New Jersey|Teterboro]]. Turning east, the freeway runs through South Hackensack before entering Hackensack, where an exit provides access to CR&nbsp;124 (Hudson Street).<ref name=sld /> The road passes near neighborhoods before crossing the [[Hackensack River]] into [[Ridgefield Park, New Jersey|Ridgefield Park]], where it passes over NYSW's New Jersey Subdivision line and [[CSX]]'s [[River Subdivision (CSX Transportation)|River Subdivision]] line before there is an exit for 2nd Street.<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> The freeway passes through a corner of [[Bogota, New Jersey|Bogota]] before it continues into [[Teaneck, New Jersey|Teaneck]].<ref name=sld /><ref name=gm /> In Teaneck, I-80 reaches its eastern terminus at the interchange with [[Interstate 95 in New Jersey|I-95]] (the [[New Jersey Turnpike]]). From here, one can head southbound on I-95 and the turnpike towards Newark, or head northbound towards the [[George Washington Bridge]] and [[New York City]].<ref name=gm />\n\n== History ==\nA freeway along the I-80 corridor was first planned in 1936 as a replacement for the cross-state US&nbsp;46, running from the George Washington Bridge west to the Delaware Water Gap and [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |title = Freeways Are Now Urged |newspaper = The New York Times |date = December 13, 1936 |page = 16 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> This proposal was considered again in 1955. Coming off the George Washington Bridge, Route&nbsp;4 and US&nbsp;46 already provided high-speed corridors, but they were overloaded, and so a new corridor in between, the Bergen-Passaic Expressway, was planned to run from the bridge to Paterson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/07/01/305699792.html|title=FREEWAY ROUTE IN JERSEY GIVEN; Fewer Protests Than Were Expected Are Voiced Over Bergen-Passaic Artery FORT LEE ENGLEWOOD LEONIA TEANECK BOGOTA RIDGEFIELD PARK HACKENSACK LODI SADDLE BROOK PATERSON WEST PATERSON TOTOWA AND WAYNE TOWNSHIP|date=July 1, 1956|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=js>{{cite book|title=Joint Study of Arterial Facilities|publisher=[[Port of New York Authority]] and [[Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority]] |year=1955}}</ref> The planned route west to the Delaware Water Gap was designated in 1956 as Federal Aid Interstate Route&nbsp;101 by the [[New Jersey State Highway Department]].<ref name=nyt2>{{cite news |last = Wright |first = George Cable |title = Jersey Acts to Speed U.S. Aid for Its $388.5 Million Freeway |newspaper = The New York Times |date = March 5, 1958 |page = |issn = 0362-4331 }}{{page needed|date=July 2019}}</ref> It first received the I-82 designation before finally becoming a part of I-80 in 1958.<ref name=\"1957 map\">{{cite map |author = [[Public Roads Administration]] |author2 = [[American Association of State Highway Officials]] |year = 1957 |title = Official Numbering for the National System of Interstate and Defense Highways, as Adopted by the American Association of State Highway Officials, August 14, 1957 |url = https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Interstate_Highway_plan_August_14,_1957.jpg |scale = Scale not given |location = Washington, DC |publisher = [[Federal Works Agency]] |accessdate =January 13, 2010 |via = [[Wikimedia Commons]] }}</ref><ref name=nyt3>{{cite news |last = Wright |first = George Cable |title = New Roads with New Numbers Will Parallel Old U.S. Routes |newspaper = The New York Times |date = September 19, 1958 |page = 29|issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> The easternmost section of the route, leading to the bridge, had become part of I-95.<ref name=nyt3 />\n\nThe section of I-80 through the Delaware Water Gap had already opened on December 16, 1953, running from the Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge to Route&nbsp;94 at Columbia.<ref name=nyt4>{{cite news |title = New Span Crosses Delaware River; Fine, Driscoll at Ceremonies for Water Gap Bridge\u2014Road to Link Poconos and New York |newspaper = The New York Times |date = December 17, 1953 |page = 51 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> This road was signed as a realignment of [[U.S. Route 611|US&nbsp;611]] from Pennsylvania, later receiving the I-80 designation. The old alignment of US&nbsp;611 in Pennsylvania had become US&nbsp;611 Alternate.<ref name=\"PennDOT 1950 back\">{{cite map|publisher=Pennsylvania Department of Highways|title=Official Road Map of Pennsylvania (back)| url=http://www.dot7.state.pa.us/BPR_PDF_FILES/MAPS/Statewide/Historic_OTMs/1950bk.pdf|year=1950|accessdate=January 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"esso\" /> By 1966, I-80 had been completed from Netcong to Denville and from Paterson to I-95.<ref name=\"esso\">{{cite map |author1 = [[Esso]] |title = United States featuring the Interstate Highway System |year = 1966 |author2 = [[General Drafting]] |scale = |location = |publisher = }}{{full|date= July 2019}}</ref> By 1969, the section between I-280 in Parsippany and Route&nbsp;23 in Wayne was finished. Also around this time, US&nbsp;611 was moved off of I-80 and back into Pennsylvania, replacing US&nbsp;611 Alternate.<ref name=\"chevron\">{{cite map |author1 = [[Chevron Oil Company]] |title = Map of New Jersey |year = 1969 |author2=[[H.M. Gousha]] |scale = |location = |publisher = }}{{full|date= July 2019}}</ref> By 1971, the section between Wayne and [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]] was completed along with the part between US&nbsp;202 and I-280.<ref name=nyt5>{{cite news |last = Shipler |first = David K. |title = New Highways Shaping Future of City's Suburbs; New Superhighways Shaping Future of City's Suburbs |newspaper = The New York Times |date = August 19, 1971 |page = 1 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> A {{convert|3.5|mi|km|adj=on}} section between US&nbsp;46 in [[Denville, New Jersey|Denville]] and US&nbsp;202 [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany-Troy Hills]], was opened in September 1973.<ref name=nyt6>{{cite news |last = Burks |first = Edward C. |title = Vital Stretch of Route 80 Opens in Jersey, Ending Big Bottleneck; Stretch of Route 80 Opens and Eliminates Bottleneck |newspaper = The New York Times |date = September 15, 1973 |page = 65 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> Also in 1973, the section between US&nbsp;206 in Netcong and US&nbsp;46 and Route&nbsp;94 in Columbia was completed, and the interchange in Columbia was realigned into a complex array of ramps.<ref name=nyt7>{{cite news |title = Missing Link of I-80 Opened in Ceremony Near Columbia |newspaper = [[The New York Times]] |date = November 9, 1973 |page = 86 |issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, two rest areas along I-80 were shut down due to chronic use for homosexual activities. The rest area in [[Lodi, New Jersey|Lodi]], next to westbound exit&nbsp;63, shut down on June 30, 1982 on request of the [[New Jersey State Police]]. Local lawyers noted that an uptick of summons were given at the rest area, including one motorist cited for not using parking lights. The State Police decided that it was not worth patrolling as it was an unattended rest area.<ref>{{cite news |title = Controversial Rest Site on Interstate is Closed |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14384914/i80_lodi_rest_area_july_8_1982/ |access-date= October 13, 2017 |work = [[The Asbury Park Press]] |date = July 8, 1982 |page = 48 |via = [[Newspapers.com]] }} {{open access}}</ref> The rest area at [[Roxbury, New Jersey|Roxbury]] in [[Morris County, New Jersey|Morris County]] shut down in October 1982.<ref name=\"roxburycloses\">{{cite news |last1 = Mitkwoski |first1 = Michelle |title = Route 80 'Gay' Spots Shut for Time Being |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14385547/80_roxbury_closed_october_30_1982/ |access-date = October 13, 2017 |work = The Daily Record |location = |date = October 30, 1982 |page = 22 |via = Newspapers.com }} {{open access}}</ref> Opened in the 1970s, the borough noted that it was impossible to control the activity going on at the location, including homosexual activities, alcohol and drug parties, theft and lewd acts.<ref name=\"roxburyproposals\">{{cite news |last1 = McKeel |first1 = Stuart |title = Roxbury Twp. Fights Proposal for Rest Areas |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14385260/roxbury_stop_june_10_1990/ |access-date = October 13, 2017 |work = The Daily Record |date = June 10, 1990 |page = 3 |via = Newspapers.com }} {{open access}}</ref> However, citing numerous accidents and needing a place for trucks to be able to rest,<ref name=\"roxburyproposals\" /> the stop re-opened on August 14, 1991 for truckers only.<ref name=\"roxburyreopens\">{{cite news |last1 = McKeel |first1 = Stuart |title = Rt. 80 Rest Area Reopens\u2014for Trucks |url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/14384940/roxbury_reopens_august_14_1991/ |access-date = October 13, 2017 |work = The Daily Record |date = August 14, 1991 |via = Newspapers.com }} {{open access}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, [[high-occupancy vehicle lane]]s were built along I-80 between Rockaway and Parsippany. These HOV lanes, along with the ones that had been built on I-287, were opened to regular traffic in 1998 due to lack of usage, and the state did not have to repay the federal government the $240&nbsp;million to build the lanes.<ref name=nyt8>{{cite news |last = Berger |first = Joseph |title = Our Towns; H.O.V. Lanes: A 30-Mile Test That Failed |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/01/nyregion/our-towns-hov-lanes-a-30-mile-test-that-failed.html |newspaper = The New York Times |date = December 1, 1998 |access-date = December 22, 2009 }}</ref> On June 22, 2001, a tanker crashed on a westbound bridge on I-80 in Denville, causing a fiery explosion that damaged the bridge and forced its demolition.<ref name=nyt9>{{cite news |last = Murphy |first = Dean E. |title = Drivers May Face Months of Delays After Fiery Crash Forces Demolition of I-80 Span |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/24/nyregion/drivers-may-face-months-delays-after-fiery-crash-forces-demolition-80-span.html |newspaper = The New York Times |date = June 24, 2001 |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref> A temporary bridge had to be built and traffic on this part of I-80 as well as adjacent roads was snarled; in addition, a state of emergency had been declared for Morris County.<ref name=nyt10>{{cite news |department = Metro Briefing |title = New Jersey: Trenton: Route 80 Emergency Declared |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/04/nyregion/metro-briefing-new-jersey-trenton-route-80-emergency-declared.html |newspaper = The New York Times |date = July 4, 2001 |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref> The new I-80 bridge opened in September 2001.<ref name=njdot>{{cite press release |author = New Jersey Department of Transportation |url = http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/about/press/2001/090501c.shtm |title = NJDOT Will Begin Work to Re-Open I-80 in Morris County |date = September 5, 2001 |publisher = New Jersey Department of Transportation |access-date = January 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nI-80, like many other highways in New Jersey, once had solar powered emergency [[call box]]es every {{convert|1|mi|km}}, however with the advent of cell phones the usage of these call boxes became extremely limited. To save on maintenance costs, the NJDOT removed these call boxes in 2005.<ref name=pressac>{{cite news |last = Barlas |first = Thomas |title = Last Call for N.J.'s Roadside Call Boxes |work = [[The Press of Atlantic City]] |date = February 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, NJDOT held a public meeting regarding a proposed rock wall along I-80 in the Delaware Water Gap National Recreation Area. The $60 million project, dubbed the \"Jurassic Park fence\", would involve construction of a {{convert|60|ft|m|adj=on}} metal fence between mile marker 1.04 and 1.05 to prevent rocks from falling onto the highway. According to NJDOT, the area has the highest rockfall hazard in the state. Nine rockfall incidents and one fatality have been reported between 2001 and 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cassi |first1=Sarah |title=Controversial I-80 project in Delaware Water Gap, dubbed the 'Jurassic Park fence,\u2019 goes before the public |url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/warren-county/2019/06/controversial-i-80-project-in-delaware-water-gap-dubbed-the-jurassic-park-fence-goes-before-the-public.html |accessdate=August 22, 2019 |agency=lehighvalleylive.com |date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Exit list ==\n{{jcttop|exit|state=NJ|length_ref=<ref name=sld />}}\n{{jctint|exit\n|river=[[Delaware River]]\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.00\n|mspan=2\n|exit=\u2013\n|road={{jct|state=PA|I|80|dir1=west|PA|611|to2=yes|city1=Stroudsburg|city2=Delaware Water Gap}}\n|notes=Continuation into [[Pennsylvania]]; toll booths across state line\n}}\n{{jctbridge|exit\n|mile=none\n|line=yes\n|type=toll\n|bridge=[[Delaware Water Gap Toll Bridge]] (Westbound toll, cash or [[E-ZPass]])}}\n{{NJint|exit\n|county=Warren\n|cspan=9\n|location=Hardwick Township\n|lspan=2\n|mile=0.10\n|exit=1\n|road=[[Millbrook, New Jersey|Millbrook]], [[Flatbrookville, New Jersey|Flatbrookville]]\n|notes=Via 